<TEXT>
<FRONT><DIV ANA="MS.Dd.3.53" TYPE="prologue">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tractatus de Conclusionibus Astrolabii.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">[Bred and mylk for childeren.]</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="1" UNIT="folio">
<P>LItell Lowys my sone, I haue perceiued well by certeyne
euidences thine abilite to lerne sciencez touchinge noumbres &amp; 
proporciouns; &para; &amp; as wel considere I thy bisi preyere in
special to lerne the tretis of the astrelabie. &para; than, for as mechel as
a philosofre seith, &para; he wrappeth him in his frend, &thorn;at 
condescendith to the rihtful preiers of his frend / ther-for haue I geuen 
the a suffisaunt astralabie as for owre orizonte, compowned after the latitude
of Oxenford / vp-on which, by mediacion of this litel tretis, I
purpose to teche the a certein nombre of conclusions apertenyng to
the same instrument.  &para; I seye a certein of couclusiouns, for thre
causes.  &para; the furste cause is this:  &para; truste wel &thorn;at alle 
the conclusiouns that han ben fownde, or elles possibli myhten be fownde
in so noble an instrument as an astralabie, ben vn-knowe perfitly to
any mortal man in this regioun, as I suppose.  &para; a-nother cause is
this ; &thorn;at sothly, in any tretis of the astrelabie &thorn;at I haue 
seyn, there ben some conclusions &thorn;at wole nat in alle thinges performen
hir byhestes;
<PB N="2">&para; &amp; some of hem ben to harde to thy tendre age of .x. yer
to conseyue.  &para; this tretis, diuided in 5 parties, wole I shewe the
vnder ful lihte rewles &amp; naked wordes in englissh ; for latyn ne
kanstow yit but smal, my lite sone.  &para; but natheles, suffise to the
thise trewe conclusiouns in englissh, as wel as suffisith to thise noble
clerkes grekes thise same conclusiouns in grek, &para; &amp; to arabiens in
arabik, &para; &amp; to Iewes in Ebrew, &amp; to the latyn folk in latyn / 
whiche latyn folk han hem furst owt of othre diuerse langages, &amp; writen in
hir owne tonge, &thorn;at is to sein, in latyn.  &para; &amp; god wot, 
&thorn;at in alle this[e] langages, &amp; in many mo, han thise conclusiouns 
ben suffisantly lerned &amp; tawht / &amp; yit by diuerse rewles, ryht as 
diuerse pathes leden diuerse folk the rihte wey to Roome.  &para; Now wol I
prey mekly euery discret persone &thorn;at redith or herith this litel tretis,
to haue my rewde endytyng for excused, &amp; my superfluite of wordes,
for two causes.  &para; the firste cause is, for that curio[u]s enditing &amp;
hard sentence Is ful heuy atones for swich a child to lerne.  &para; &amp;
the seconde cause is this, &thorn;at sothly me semeth betre to writen vn-to
a child twies a good sentence, than he for-get it ones.  &para; And lowis,
&yogh;if so be &thorn;at I shewe the in my lihte Englissh as trewe conclusiouns
touching this matere, &amp; nawht only as trewe but as many &amp; as subtil
conclusiouns as ben shewed in latyn <MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio">in ani commune tretis of the astrelabie / kon me the more thank ; 
&para; and preye god saue the
kyng, &thorn;at is lord of this langage, &amp; alle that him feyth bereth 
&amp; obeieth, euerech in his degree, the more and the lasse. &para; but 
considere wel, that I ne vsurpe nat to haue fownde this werk of my labour 
or of myn engin.  &para; I nam but a lewd compilatour of the labour of olde 
Astrolog[i]ens, and haue hit translated in myn englissh only for thi doctrine 
; &para; &amp; with this swerd shal I slen envie.
</P><PB N="3"><P>&para; The firste partie of this tretis shal reherse the figures &amp; the
membres of thin Astrolabie, by-cause &thorn;at thow shalt han the grettre
knowyng of thin owne instrument.
</P><P>&para; The second partie shal teche the werken the verrey practik of
the forseide conclusiouns, as ferforth &amp; as narwe as may be shewyd
in so smal an instrument portatif a-boute. &para; For wel wot euery 
astrologien &thorn;at smalest fraccions ne wol nat ben shewid in so smal an 
instrument, as in subtil tables calkuled for a kawse.
</P><P>&para; The .3. partie shal contienen diuerse tables of longitudes &amp; 
latitudes of sterres fixe for the Astrolabie, &para; &amp; tables of 
declinacions of the [sonne], &amp; tables of longitudes of Citeez &amp; of 
townes ; &para; &amp; as wel for the gouernance of a clokke as for to fynde 
the altitude Meridian / 
&amp; many [a]-nother notable conclusioun, aftur the kalendres of the
reuerent clerk[e]s, frere I. Somer &amp; frere N. Lenne.
</P><P>&para; The .4. partie shal ben a theorik to declare the Moeuynge of
the celestial bodies with [&thorn;e] causes. &para; the whiche 4 partie in 
special shal shewen a table of the verray Moeuyng of the Mone from howre
to howre, euery day <MILESTONE N="2" UNIT="folio">&amp; in euery signe, after thin Almenak / 
vp-on wych table ther folwith a canon, suffisant to teche as wel the
maner  of the wyrkyng of &thorn;at same conclusioun / as to knowe in
owre orizonte with wych degree of the zodiac that the Mone arisith
in any latitude / &amp; the arising of any planete aftur his latitude fro
the Ecliptik lyne.
</P><P>&para; The .5. partie shal ben an introductorie aftur the statutz of owre
doctours, in which thow maist lerne a gret part of the general rewles
of theorik in Astrologie.  &para; in which .5. partie shaltow fynde tables
of equacions of howses aftur &thorn;e latitude of Oxenford; &para; &amp; 
tables of dignetes of planetes / &amp; other noteful thingez / yif god wol 
vouche sauf &amp; his modur the mayde, mo than I be-hete, &amp;c.
</P>
</DIV></FRONT><BODY>
<DIV0 TYPE="part"><PB N="4"><HEAD>Her by-gynneth the descripcion of the Astrelabie.</HEAD>
<DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>1.</HEAD><P>&para; Thyn Astrelabie hath a ring to putten on the t[h]owmbe of
thy ryht hand in takyng the heyhte of thynges. &para; &amp; tak kep, for
from hennes-forthward, I wol clepe tho heyhte of any thing &thorn;at is
taken by thy rewle, the altitude, with-owte mo wordes.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>2.</HEAD>
<P>&para; This ring rennyth in A Maner turet, fast to the Moder of
thyn Astrelabie, in so Rowm a space &thorn;at hit desturbith nat the 
instrument to hangen aftur his rihte centre.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>3.</HEAD><P>&para; The moder of thin Astrelabie is [&thorn;e] thikkeste plate,
perced with a large hole, &thorn;at resseyuyth in hir wombe the thynne
plates compowned for diuerse clymatz, &amp; thi Riet shapen in manere
of a net or of a webbe of a loppe ; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo
here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>4.</HEAD><P>&para; This Moder is deuyded on the bakhalf with a lyne, &thorn;at
cometh dessendinge fro the ryng down to the nethereste bordure.
&para; the whiche lyne, fro &thorn;e for-seide Ryng vn-to the centre of the 
large hole amydde, is cleped the sowth lyne, or elles the lyne Meridional.
&para; &amp; the remenant of this lyne downe to the bordure is cleped the
north lyne, or elles the lyne of Midnyht.  &para; &amp; for the more 
declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="5"><MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>5.</HEAD><P>&para; Ouer-thwart this for-seide longe lyne, ther crosseth hym
a-nother lyne of the same lengthe from est to west.  Of the whiche
lyne, from a lityl croys + in the bordure vn-to the centre of the large
hole, is cleped the Est lyne, or elles the lyne Orientale ; &para; &amp; the
remenant of this lyne fro the forseide + vn-to the bordure, is cleped
the west lyne, or the lyne occidentale.  &para; now hastow her the 4
quarters of thin astrelabie, deuyded after the 4 principals plages or
quarters of the firmament.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here
thi figure. </P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>6.</HEAD><P>&para; The est side of thin Astrelabie is cleped the riht side, &para; 
&amp; the west side is cleped the left side. &para; for-get nat this, 
lite[l] lowys.  &para; put the ring of thin Astralabie vp-on the thowmbe of thy ryht
hand, and thanne wole his right side be toward thy left side, &amp; his
left side wol be toward thy right side ; tak this rewle general, as wel
on the bak as on the wombe-side.  &para; vp-on the ende of this est
lyne, as I first seide, is marked a litel +, wher as euere-mo generaly
is considered the entring of the first degree in wich the sonne arisith.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here &thorn;e figure. </P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE
N="3b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>7.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Fro this litel + vp to the ende of the lyne Meridional, vndur the ryng, &para; shaltow fynden the bordure deuyded with
90 degres ; &amp; by that same proporcioun is euery quarter of thin Astrolabie deuyded.  &para; ouer the wiche degrees ther ben nowmbres of
augrym, &thorn;at deuyden thilke same degres fro 5 to 5, as shewith by
longe strykes bytwene.  &para; of wyche longe strykes the space by-
twene contienith a Mile-wey.  &para; &amp; euery degree of the bordure
contieneth 4 Minutes, that [is] to seyn, minutes of an howre. &para; &amp;
for more declaracioun, lo here the figure. </P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="6"><MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>8.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Vnder the compas of thilke degres ben writen the
names of the 12 signes, as Aries, taurus, gemini, Cancer, leo, virgo,
libra, Scorpio, Sagittarius, Capricornus, Aquarius, Pisces  &amp; the
nombres of the degres of tho signes ben writen in Augrim aboue, &amp;
with longe deuysiouns, fro 5 to 5 ; deuyded fro tyme &thorn;at the signe
entreth vn-to the laste ende. &para; but vndorstond wel, &thorn;at thise 
degrees of signes ben euerich of hem considered of 60 Mynutes, &amp; euery
Minute of 60 secondes, &amp; so forth in-to smale fraccions infinit, as
seith Alkabucius. &para; &amp; ther-for, know wel, &thorn;at a degree of the 
bordure contienith 4 Minutis, and a degre of a signe contienith 60 Mynutis,
&amp; haue this in Mynde. &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thi
figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>9.</HEAD><P>&para; Next this folwyth the cercle of the dayes, &thorn;at ben figured
in maner of degrees, &thorn;at contienen in nowmbre 365 ; dyuyded also
with longe strikes fro 5 to 5, &amp; the nombre[s] in Augrym writen
vnder &thorn;at cercle.  &para; and for more declaracioun, loo heere thy 
figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>10.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Next the cercle of tho dayes folweth the Cercle of
the names of the Monthes ; &thorn;at is to seyen, Ianuare, Februare,
Marcius, Aprile, Mayus, Iuyn, Iulius, Augustus, Septembre, October, Novembre, Decembre. &para; the names of thise Monthes were cleped
in Arabyens, somme for hir propretes, &amp; some by statutz of lordes,
some by other lordes of Rome. &para; ek of thise Monthes, as liked to
Iulius cesar &amp; to cesar Augustus, some were compowned of diuerse
nombres of dayes, as Iuyl and August. &para; thanne hath Ianuare xxxi
daies, Februare 28, March 31, Aprille 30, May 31, Iunius 30, Iulius
31, Augustus 31, September 30, Octobre 3l, Nouembre 30, December 31. &para; natheles, al-thow that Iulius cesar tok 2 daies owt of
Feuerer &amp; put hem in his monith of Iuylle, &amp; Augustus cesar cleped
<PB N="7">the Monyth of August After his name &amp; ordeyned it of 31 daies, yit
truste wel, &thorn;at the sonne dwelleth ther-for neuere the more ne lesse
in on signe than in another.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>11.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Than folwen the names of the halidayes in the kalender
&amp; next hem the lettres of the A. b. c. on wich they fallen. &para; &amp; 
for the more declaracioun, loo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>12.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Next the forseide cercle of the A. b. c., vnder the
cros-lyne, is Marked the skale, in Maner of 2 Squyres or elles in
Manere of laddres, &thorn;at seruith by hise 12 poyntes &amp; hise deuisiouns
of ful many a subtil conclusioun.  Of this forseide skale, fro the
croos-lyne vn-to the verre angle, is clepid <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">vmbra [versa]</FOREIGN>, &amp; the nether
partie is cleped the <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">vmbra [recta</FOREIGN>, or elles <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">umbra extensa</FOREIGN>.]  &para; &amp; for
the more declaracioun, loo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>13.</HEAD><P>&para; Thanne hastow a brod Rewle, &thorn;at hath on either ende a
Square plate perced with a certein holes, some more &amp; some lesse, to
resseyuen the stremes of the sonne by day, and ek by mediacioun of
<PB N="8">thyn Eye, to knowe the altitude of sterres by nyhte &para;{ &amp; for the
more declaracioun, lo here thi figure
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>14.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Thanne is ther a large Pyn in maner of an Extre, &thorn;at goth
thorow the hole / that halt the tables of the clymates &amp; the Riet in
the wombe of the Moder / thorw wich pyn ther goth a litel wegge
which &thorn;at is cleped the hors, &thorn;at streynet[h] alle thise parties 
to hepe ; this forseide grete Pyn in maner of an extre is ymagyn[e]d to be the
Pol Artyk in thin Astralabie.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo
here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>15.</HEAD>
<P>&para; The wombe-side of thyne Astrelabie is also deuyded wit[h] a longe croys in 4 quarters from est to West, fro sowth
to north, fro riht side to left side, as is the bak-side. &amp; for the more
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>16.</HEAD><P>&para; The bordure of which wombe-side is deuyded fro the
poynt of the est lyne vn-to the poynt of the south lyne vnder the
ring, in 90 degres ; &amp; by &thorn;at same proporcioun is euery quarter deuyded as ys the bak-side, &thorn;at amonteth 360 degres.  &para; &amp; 
vnderstond wel, &thorn;at degres of this Bordure ben answering &amp; 
consentrik to the degrees of the Equynoxial, &thorn;at ys deuyded in the same 
nombre as euery othere cercle is in the heie heuene.  &para; This same bordure
is deuyded also with 23 lettres capitals &amp; a smal croys + aboue the
south lyne, &thorn;at shewith the 24 howres equals of the clokke / &amp;, as I
haue said, 5 of thise degrees maken a Milewey, &amp; 3 Milewey maken
an howre. &para; &amp; euery degree of this bordure contineth 4 Mynutes, &amp;
<PB N="9">euery Minut 60 secoundes ; now haue [y] told the twye &para; &amp; for the
more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>17.</HEAD><P>&para; The plate vnder thi Riet is descriued with 3 [principal] cerclis ; of wiche the leste is cleped the cercle of cancer / by-cause &thorn;at the heued of cancer turnyth euermor consentrik vp-on the
same cercle.  &para; in this heued of cancer is the grettest declinacioun
northward of the sonne.  &para; &amp; ther-for is he cleped the Solsticioun
of somer; &para; wiche declinacioun , aftur ptholome, is 23 degrees &amp; 50
Minutis, as wel in cancer as in Capricorne. this signe of cancre is
cleped the tropik of Somer, of <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">tropos</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at is to seyn  Agaynward, for
thanne by-gynneth the sonne to passe fro vs-ward ; &para; &amp; for the
more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P><MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio"><P>&para; The Middel cercle in wydnesse, of thise 3, is cleped
the cercle equinoxial / vp-on whiche turneth euermo the hedes of
aries &amp; libra.  &para; &amp; vnderstond wel, &thorn;at euermo this cercle 
equinoxial turnyth Iustly fro verrey est to verrey west; &para; as I haue
shewed the in the sper solide.  &para; this same cercle is cleped also the
weyere, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">equator</FOREIGN>, of the day / for whan the sonne is in the heuedes of aries &amp; libra, than ben the daies &amp; the nyht[es] illike of lenghthe in
al the world.  &para; &amp; ther-fore ben thise two signes called the equinoxiis.  &para; &amp; alle &thorn;at Moeuyth with-in the heuedes of thise aries &amp;
libra, his Moeuyng is cleped north-ward / &amp; alle that Moeuyth withoute thise heuedes, his Moeuyng is clepid sowth-ward as fro the
equinoxial.  &para; tak kep of thise latitudes north and sowth, &amp; for-get
it nat.  &para; by this cercle equinoxial ben considered the 24 howres of
the clokke ; for eueremo the  arisyng of 15 degrees of the equinoxial
maketh an howre equal of the clokke.  &para; this equinoxial is cleped
<PB N="10">the gyrdelle of the firste Moeuyng, or elles of the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">angulus primi motus vel primi mobilis</FOREIGN>.  And nota, &thorn;at firste Moeuyng is cleped "Moeuyng" of the firste Moeuable of the 8 spere, whiche Moeuyng is fro est to west, &para; &amp; eft agayn in-to est / also it is clepid "girdel" of the first Moeuyng, for it departeth the furste Moeuable, &thorn;at is to seyn, the spere, in 2 ilike parties, euene distantz fro the poles of this world.  
</P><P>&para;The wydeste of thise 3 principal cerkles is cleped the cercle of capricorne, by-cause &thorn;at the heued of capricorne turnyth euermo consentryk vp-on the same cercle / in the heued of this for-seide capricorne is the grettest declinacioun sowthward of the sonne, &amp; ther-for is it cleped the solsticioun of wyntur.  this signe of capricorne is also cleped the tropik of wyntur, for thanne bygynnyth the sonne to come agayn to vs-ward.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>18.</HEAD><P>&para; Vp-on this forseide plate ben compassed certein cerclis &thorn;at hihten Almicanteras / of which som of hem semen perfit cercles, &amp; somme semen inperfit.  the centre &thorn;at standith a-Middes the narwest cercle is cleped the senyth; &para; &amp; the netherest cercle, or the furste cercle, is clepid the orisonte, &para; &thorn;at is to seyn, the cercle<PB
N="11"> &thorn;at deuydeth the two Emysperies / &thorn;at is, the partie of the heuene a-boue the Erthe &amp; the partie be-nethe.  &para; thise almy-kanteras ben compowned by 2 &amp; 2, al be it so &thorn;at on diuers Astrelabies some almy-kanteras ben deuyded by on / &amp; some by two, &amp; somme by .3. aftur the quantite of the Astrelabie.  &amp; this forseide cenyth is ymagened to ben the verrey point ouer the crowne of thyn heued / &amp; also this senyth is the verrey pool of the orisonte in euery regioun.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>19.</HEAD><P>&para; From this senyth, as it semeth, ther come a maner krokede strikes like to the clawes of a loppe, or elles like to the werk of a womanes calle, in keruyng ouerthwart the Almykanteras.  &para; &amp; thise same strikes or diuisiouns ben cleped Azymuthz.  &para; &amp; they deuyden the Orisonte of thin astrelabie in 24 deuisiouns.  &para; &amp; thise A&yogh;imutz seruen to knowe the costes of the firmament &para; &amp; to othre conclusiouns, as for to knowe the cenyth of the sonne &amp; of euery sterre.  &para; &amp; for [the] more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>20.</HEAD><P>&para; Next thise azymutz, vnder the cercle of Cancer, ben ther 12 deuysiouns embelif, moche like to the shap of the azimutes, &thorn;at shewen the spaces of the howres of planetes / &amp; for mor declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P>
</DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>21.</HEAD><P>&para; The riet of thin Astrelabie with thy zokiak, shapen in maner of a net or of a lop-webbe aftur the olde descripcioun, which thow maist tornen vp and down as thi-self likyth, contienith certein nombre of sterres fixes, with hir longitudes &amp; latitudes determynat;
<PB N="12">&para; &yogh;if so be &thorn;at the makere haue nat erred.  the names of 
the sterres ben writen in the Margyn of the riet ther as they sitte; &para; 
Of whiche sterres the smale poynt is cleped the Centre / And vnderstond also
&thorn;ot alle sterres sittinge wyth-in the zodiak of thin astrolabie ben
cleped sterres of the north, &para; For thei Arisen by northe the est lyne.
&para; &amp; alle the remenant fixed, owt of the zodiak, ben cleped sterres of
the sowth; &para; but y sey nat &thorn;at they arisen alle by southe the est
lyne ; witnesse on aldeberan &amp; Algomeysa.  &para; generally vnderstond
this rewle, that thilke sterres &thorn;at ben cleped sterres of the north
arisen rather than the degree of hire longitude, &amp; alle [the] sterres of
the sowth arisen aftur the degree of hire longitude; this is to seyn,
sterres fixed in thin Astralabie. the mesure of this longitude of
sterres is taken in the lyne Eclyptik of heuene, vnder which lyne,
whan that the sonne &amp; the Mone ben lyne-riht or elles in the
superfice of this lyne / than is the Eclips of the sonne or of the
Mone ; as y shal declare, &amp; ek the cause why. but <MILESTONE
N="8" UNIT="folio">sothly the Ecliptik lyne of thy zodiak is the owttereste bordure of thy zodiak,
ther the degrees ben marked.
</P><P>&para; Thy zodiak of thin Astralabie is shapen as a compas wich &thorn;at
contienith a large brede, as aftur the quantite of thin astralabie / in
ensample &thorn;at the zodiak in heuene is ymagened to ben a superfice
contienyng a latitude of 12 degrees, &para; wher[as] al the remenant of
cerkles in the heuene ben ymagined verrey lynes with-owte eny
latitude.  &para; Amiddes this celestial zodiak ys ymagined a lyne, which
&thorn;at is cleped the Ecliptik lyne / vndur which lyne is euermo the
wey of the sonne.  &para; Thus ben ther 6 degrees of the zodiak on &thorn;at
on side of the lyne, and 6 degrees on that other.  &para; This zodiak is
<PB N="13">deuided in 12 principa1 deuisiouns, &thorn;at departen the 12 signes. &para;
&amp;, for the streitnes of thin astrelabie, than is euery smal deuysioun in a
signe departid by two degrees &amp; two; I Mene degrees contenyng 60
Minutes.  &para; &amp; this forseide heuenissh zodiak is cleped the cercle of
the signes / or the cercle of the bestes / for <HI REND="i">zodia</HI> in langage of grek sownyth `bestes' in latyn tonge.  &para; &amp; in the zodiak ben the 12
signes &thorn;at han names of bestes; or elles for whan the sonne entrith
in any of the signes, he taketh the proprete of swich bestes ; or
elles for &thorn;at the sterres that ben there fixed ben disposed in signes of
bestes, &para; or shape like bestes; &para; or elles whan the planetes ben vnder
thilke signes, &thorn;ei causen vs by hir influence operaciouns &amp; effectes
lik to the operaciouns of bestes.  &para; &amp; vnderstonde Also, &thorn;at 
whan an hot planete comyth in-to an hot signe, than encresseth his hete; &amp;
&yogh;if a planete be cold, thanne amenuseth his coldnesse, by-cause of the
hote signe.  &para; &amp; by this conclusioun maistow take ensample in alle
the signes, be they moist or drie, or moeble or fix; rekenyng the
qualite of the planete as I furst seide. &para; &amp; euerich of thise 12 
Signes hath respecte to a certein parcelle of the body of a man and hath it
in gouernance; as aries hath thin heued, &amp; taurus thy nekke &amp; thy
throte / gemyni thyn armholes &amp; thin armes, &para; &amp; so forth; as
shal be shewed more pleyn in the 5 partie of this tretis. this zodiak,
which &thorn;at is part of the 8 spere, ouer-kerueth the equinoxial; and
he ouer-kerueth hym again in euene parties / &amp; &thorn;at on half declinith
sowthward, &amp; &thorn;at other northward, as pleynli declareth the tretis of
the spere.  &para; &amp; for mor declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD>22.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Thanne hastow a label, &thorn;at is schapen lik a rewle,
<PB N="14">saue &thorn;at it is streit &amp; hath no plates on either ende with holes ;
&para; but with the smale point of the forseide label, shaltow kalcule
thyne equaciouns in the bordure of thin Astrolabie as bi thin almury.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thy figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><HEAD>23.</HEAD><P>&para; Thin almury is cleped the denticle of capricorne or elles
the kalkuler.  &para; this same Almury sit fix in the hed of capricorne, &amp; it seruyth of many a necessarie conclusioun in equaciouns
of thynges, as shal be shewed; &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here
thi figure.
</P>
</DIV1><CLOSER>Her endith the descripcion of the Astrelabie.</CLOSER></DIV0>
<DIV0 TYPE="part"><MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>Her bygynnen the conclusions of the Astrelabie.</HEAD>
<DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>1. To fynde the degree in which the sonne is day by day,
after hir cours a-bowte.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Hic incipiunt conclusiones astrolabii; &amp; prima est ad inveniendum gradus solis in quibus singulis diebus secundum cursum
sol est existens.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Rekene and knowe which is the day of thi monthe &para; &amp; ley
thi reule vp that same day, &amp; thanne wol the verray point of thy
rewle sitten in the bordure, vp-on the degree of thy sonne.  &para; Ensample as thus ; the yer of oure lord 1391, the 12 day of March at
Midday, I wolde knowe the degree of the sonne.  &para; I sowhte in the
bakhalf of myn astrelabie, and fond the sercle of the daies, &para; the
which I knowe by the names of the Monthes writen vndur the same
Cercle.  &para; Tho leide I my rewle ouer this forseide day, &amp; fond the
<PB N="15">point of my rewle in the bordure vp-on the firste degree of aries, A
litel with-in the degree / &amp; thus knowe I this conclusioun. &para; A-nother
day, I wolde knowe the degree of my sonne, &amp; this was at Midday
in the 13. day of decembre ; I fond the day of the monthe in maner
as I seide / tho leide I my rewle vp-on this forseide 13. day, &amp; found
the point of my rewle in the bordure vp-on the first degree of capricorne / 
a lite with-in the degree &para; &amp; than haddy of this conclusioun the 
ful experience / &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo her thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>2. To knowe the altitude of the sonne, or of othre celestial bodies.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[De altitudine solis &amp; aliorum corporum supra celestium.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Put the ring of thin Astrelabie vp-on thi riht thowmbe &amp;
turne thi lift side a-gayn the light of the sonne/  And rem[e]ue thi
rewle vp and down til &thorn;at the stremes of the sonne shyne thorgh
bothe holes of thi rewle.  &para; loke thanne how Many degrees thi
rewle is a-reised fro the litel crois vp-on thin est line, &amp; tak ther the
altitude of thi sonne.  &para; &amp; in this same wyse maistow knowe by
nyhte the altitude of the Mone, or of brihte sterres / this chapitre
is so general euer in on, &thorn;at ther nedith no more declaracion; but
for-get it nat.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>3. To knowe euery tyme of the day by liht of the sonne,
&amp; euery tyme of the nyht by the sterres fixe, &amp; eke to knowe by
nyht or by day the degree of any signe &thorn;at assendith on the
est Orisonte, which &thorn;at is cleped communly the assendent or
elles oruscupum.</HEAD><PB N="16"><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum quidlibet tempus diei per solis indicacionem,
&amp; quodlibet tempus noctis per quasdam stellas in celo fixas;
ac eciam ad inveniendum &amp; cognoscendum signum super orizontem qui communiter vocatur ascendens.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Tak the altitude of the sonne whan the list, as I haue said ;
&para; &amp; set the degree of the sonne, in kas &thorn;at it be by-forn 
the Middel of the day, among thin al-my-kanteras on the est side of thin
astralabie ; &amp; &yogh;if it be after the Middel of the day, set the degree 
of thy sonne vp-on the west side / tak this manere of settyng for a
general rewle, ones for euere.  &para; &amp; whan thow hast set the degree
of thy sonne vp as many Almykanteras of heyhte as was the altitude of the 
sonne takyn by thi rewle, &para; ley ouer thi label, vp-on the
degree of the sonne; &para; &amp; thanne wol the point of thi label sit[t]en in
the bordure, vp-on the verrey tid of the day.   Ensample as thus /
the yer of owre lord 1391, the 12 day of March, I wold knowe the
tyd of the day.  I tok the altitude of my sonne, &para; &amp; fond &thorn;at it
was 25 degrees and 30 of Minutes of heyhte in the bordure on the
bak-side.  &para; tho turnede I Myn astrelabie, &amp; by cause that it was
by-for&nmacr; Midday, I turnede Mi riet and sette the degree of the sonne,
that is to seyn the .1. degree of Aries / on the riht side of myn
Astralabie, vp-on &thorn;at 25 degrees &amp; 30 of Minutes of heyhte among
myn almy-kanteras / tho leide I my label vp-on the degree of my
sonne, &amp; fond the poynte <MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio">of my label in the bordure, vp-on a capital lettre &thorn;at is cleped an X; tho rekened I alle the capitalles lettres fro the lyne of Midnyght vn-to this forseide lettre X, &amp; fond
&thorn;at it was 9 of the clokke of the day. tho loked I do[w]n vp-on the
Est Orisonte, and fond there the 20 degree of gemynis assending ;
<PB N="17">which &thorn;at I tok for Myn assendent. &amp; in this wyse hadde I the
experience for euer-mo in wich maner I sholde knowe the tyde of the
day / &amp; ek myn assendent.  &para; Tho wold I wyte the same nyght folwyng 
the howr of the nyght / &amp; wrowhte in this wyse / among an
hep of sterris fixe, it liked me for to take the altitude of the feire
white sterre &thorn;at is cleped Alhabor / and fond hir sitting on the west
side of the line of Midday, 18 degres of heyhte taken by my rewle
on the bak-side.  &para; tho sette I the centre of this Alhabor vp-on 18
degrees among myn Almy-kanteras, vp-on the west side ; by cause
&thorn;at she was fonden on the west side.  tho leide I my label ouer the
degree of the sonne &thorn;at was descended vnder the weste Orisonte,
&para; &amp; rikened alle the lettres capitals fro the lyne of Midday vn-to 
&thorn;e point of my label in the bordure; &para; &amp; fond &thorn;at it 
was passed 8 of  the clokke the space of 2 degrees / tho loked I doun vp-on myn est
orisonte, &para; &amp; fond ther 23 degrees of libra assending, whom I tok
for myn assendent; &amp; thus lerned I to knowe ones for euer in which
Manere I shuld come to the howre of the nyht / and to myn assendent;
as verreyli as may be taken by so smal [an] instrument / but natheles
in general wold I warne the for euere / ne mak the neuere bold to
haue take a Iust Ascendent by thin Astrilabie, or elles to haue sette
Iustly a clokke, whan any celestial body by which &thorn;at thow wenest
gouer e thilke thynges ben ney the sowth lyne / for trust wel, whan
&thorn;at &thorn;e sonne is ney the Meridional lyne, the degree of the sonne
rennyth so longe consentrik vp-on the almy-kanteras, &thorn;at sothly
thow shalt erre fro the Iust assendent / the same conclusioun sey I by
&thorn;e centre of any sterre fix by nyht; and more-ouer, by experience, I
wot wel that in owre Orisonte, from .xi. of the clokke vn-to on of the
<PB N="18">clokke, in takyng of a Iust assendent in A portatif Astrelabie, hit is
to hard to knowe.  I mene, from .xi. of the clokke by-forn the howre
of noon til on of the clok next folwyng.  &para; &amp; for the more 
declaracion, lo her thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>4. Special declaracion of the assendent.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Specialis declaracio de ascendente.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; The assendent sothly, as wel in alle natiuitez as in questiouns
&amp; elecciouns of tymes, is a thing which &thorn;at thise Astrologiens gretly
obseruen / wher-fore me semeth conuenient, sin &thorn;at I speke of the
assendent, to make of it special declaracioun / The assendent sothly,
to take it at the [largeste], is thilke degree &thorn;at assendith at any of
thise forseide tymes v[po]n the est Orisonte; &amp; there-for, yif &thorn;at 
any planet assende at &thorn;at same tyme in thilke for-seide [degre of] 
his longitude, Men seyn &thorn;at thilke planete is in <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">horoscopo</FOREIGN>. &para; but  sothly, the hows of the assendent, &thorn;at is to seyn, the firste hous or the est Angle, is a thing more brod &amp; large.  &para; For after the statutz of Astrologiens, what celestial body &thorn;at is 5 degres a-boue thilk degre &thorn;at
assendith, or with-in &thorn;at nowmbre, &thorn;at is to seyn, nere the degree
&thorn;at assendith / yit rikne thei thilke planet in the Assendent. &para; And
what planete &thorn;at is vnder thilke degree &thorn;at assendith the space 
of [25] degrees, &para; yit sein thei that thilke planete is lyk to him 
&thorn;at is [in] the hows of the assendent / but sothly, yif he passe the bondes of thise
forseide spaces, a-boue or by-nethe, they sein &thorn;at the planete is
failling fro the assendent; / yit sein thise Astrolog[i]ens, that the
assendent &para; &amp; eke the lord of the assendent, may be shapen for to
be fortunat or infortunat / as thus / a fortunat assendent clepen
they whan &thorn;at no wykkid planete, as saturne or Mars, or elles the
tail of the dragoun, is in [&thorn;e] hows <MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio">of the assendent, ne &thorn;at no wikked planete haue non aspecte of enemyte vp-on the assendent ; but they wol caste &thorn;at thei haue a fortunat planete in hir assendent
&amp; &yogh;it in his felicite, &para; &amp; than sey they &thorn;at it is 
wel.  &para; fortherouer, 
<PB N="19"> they seyn &thorn;at the infortunyng of an assendent is the contrarie of this forseide thinges.  &para; the lord of the assendent sey they &thorn;at he is fortunat, whan he is in god place fro the assendent as in angle; or in a succedent, where-as he is in his dignite &amp; conforted with frendly aspectys of planetes &amp; [wel] resceiued, &amp; ek that he may sen the assendent, and &thorn;at he be nat retrograd ne combust, ne ioigned with no shrewe in the same signe / ne that he be nat in his des[c]encioun, ne ioigned with no planete in his discencioun, ne haue vp-on him non aspecte infortunat; &amp; [than] sey they &thorn;at he is wel.  &para; natheles, theise ben obseruauncez of iudicial matiere &amp; rytes of paiens, in which my spirit ne hath no feith, ne no knowyng of hir <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">horoscopum</FOREIGN>; for they seyn &thorn;at euery signe is departid in 3 euene parties by [10] degrees, &amp; thilke porcioun they clepe a face.  &para; &amp; al-thogh &thorn;at a planete haue a latitude fro the Ecliptik, yit sey [some folk] so &thorn;at the planete arise in &thorn;at same signe wyth any degree of the forseide face in which [h]is longitude is rekned, &thorn;at yit is the planete in <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">horoscopo</FOREIGN> / be it in natiuite or in eleccioun, &amp;c. &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>5. To knowe the verrey equacioun of the degree of the sonne, yif so be &thorn;at it falle by-twixe thin Almykanteras.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum veram equacionem de gradu solis, si contigerit fore in duas Almicanteras.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE
N="12" UNIT="folio"><P>&para; For as moche as the almykanteras in thin astrelabie ben compownet by two &amp; two, &para; where-as some Almykanteras in sondri Astrelabies ben compownet by on and on, or elles by 2 &amp; 2, it is necessarie to thy lernyng to teche the first to knowe &amp; worke with thin owne Instrument.  &para; where-for, whan &thorn;at the degreee of thy sonne falleth by-twixe two Almykanteras / or elles yif thin Almykanteras ben grauen with ouer gret a point of a compas / for bothe thise thinges may causen errour as wel in knowyng of the tid of the day as of the verrey Assendent / thow Most werken in this wise.
<PB N="20">&para; Set the degree [of] thy sonne vp-on the heyer Almykanteras of
bothe / &amp; waite wel wher as thin Almury towcheth the bordure, &amp;
set ther a prikke of ynke &para; Set down agayn the degree of thy
sonne vp-on the nethere Almy-kanteras of bothe / &amp; set ther another
prikke. &para; remewe thanne thin Almury in the bordure euene amiddes bothe prikkes / &amp; this wol lede iustly the degree of thi sonne to
sitte by-twixe bothe Almykanteras in his riht place.  &para; ley thanne
thy label ouer the degree of thy sonne ; &amp; find in the bordure the
verrey tide of the day or of the nyht.  &para; &amp; as verreyly shaltow
fynde vp-on thin est orisonte thyn assendent &para; &amp; for more 
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>6. To knowe the spring of the dawyng &amp; the ende
of the euenyng, the which ben called the two crepusculus :</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum ortum solis &amp; eius occasum, que uocatur vulgariter 
crepusculum.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the nadir of thy sonne vp-on 18 degrees of heyhte /
Among thyn Almykanteras on the west side, &amp; ley thy label on &thorn;e
degre of thy sonne, &amp; thanne shal the poynt of thi label schewe the
spryng of day.  &para; Also set the nadir of thy sonne vp-on 18 degres
of heyhte a-mong thin Almykanteras on the [est] side, &amp; ley ouer
thy label vp-on the degree of the sonne / &amp; with the point of thy
label fynd in the bordure the ende of the euenyng, &thorn;at is, verrey
nyht. the nadir of the sonne is thilke degree &thorn;at is opposit to the
degree of the sonne, in the 7 signe, as thus / euery degree of aries bi
ordre is nadir to euery degree of libra by ordre / &amp; taurus to Scorpion 
/ gemini to Sagittare / Cancer to Capricorne / leo to aquarie /
virgo to pisces / &amp; &yogh;if any degree in thi zodiak be dirk, [h]is nadire
shal declare him.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo heere thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="21">
<HEAD>7. To knowe the arch of the day, that some folk kallen the day
artificial, from the sonne arisyng til hit go to rest[e].</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum archum diei, quem vu1gus vocat diem artificialem in hoc ab ortu solis vsque ad occasum.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the degree of thy sonne vp-on thin Est orisonte, &amp; ley thy
label on the degree of the sonne, &amp; at the poynt of thy label in the
bordure set a prikke.  &para; Tur&nmacr; thanne thi riet aboute til the degree
<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio">of the sonne sit vp-on the west Orisonte, &amp; ley thi label vp-on the same degree of the sonne,  &amp; at the point of thi label set a-nother prikke.  &para; rekne thanne the quantite of tyme in the bordure by-twixe bothe prikkes, &amp; tak ther thin ark of the day.  &para; the remenant of the bordure vnder the Orisonte is the ark of the nyht.  &para; thus maistow rekne  bothe arches / or euery porcion, of wheither &thorn;at the liketh. &para; &amp; by this Manere of wyrkyng / Maistow se how longe &thorn;at any sterre fix dwellith a-boue the erthe, fro tyme &thorn;at he risith til he go to rest .  &para; but the day natural, &thorn;at is to
seyn 24 houris, is the reuolucioun of the equinoxial with as moche
partie of the zodiak as the sonne of his propre Moeuinge passeth in
the mene while.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo her thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>8. To tur&nmacr; the howres in-equales in howres equales.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad conuertendum horas inequales in horas equales.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Knowe the nombre of the degrees in the howris in-equales, &amp;
departe hem by 15, &amp; tak ther thin howris equales.  [&para; &amp; for the
more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.]
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="22"><MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>9. To knowe the quantite of the day vulgare, that is to
seyen, from spring of the day vn-to verrey nyht.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum qaantitatem diei vulgaris, viz. ab ortu diei
vsque ad noctem.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Know the quantite of thi crepusculis, as I haue tawht in the
chapitre by-forn, &amp; adde hem to the arch of thi day artificial / &amp; tak
ther the space of alle the hole day vulgar, vn-to verrey nyht. / The
same manere maistow worke to knowe the quantite of the vulgar
nyht. / &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>10. To knowe the quantite of howres in-equales by day.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum horas inequale[s] in die.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Vnderstond wel, &thorn;at thise howris in-equalis ben cleped howres
of planetes, &amp; vnderstond wel &thorn;at som tyme ben thei lengere by day
[than] by nyht, &amp; som tyme the contrarie. &para; but vnderstond wel
&thorn;at euermo generaly &thorn;e howr in-equal of the [day with &thorn;e 
howr in-equal of the] nyght contenen [30] degrees of tho bordure, whiche bordure is 
euer-mo answering to the degrees of the equinoxial ; wherfor departe the arch 
of the day artificial in 12, &amp; tak ther the quantite of the howr in-equal 
by day.  &para; &amp; &yogh;if thow abate the quantite
of the howr in-equal by daye owt of 30 / than shal the remenant &thorn;at
leueth performe the howr inequal by nyght.  &para; &amp; for the more
declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>11. To knowe the quantite of howres equales.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum quantitatem horarum inequalium.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; The quantite of howres equales, &thorn;at is to seyn, the howres
of the clokke / ben departid by 15 degrees al-redy in the bordure
<PB N="23">of thin astalabie, as wel by nyht as by day, generaly for euere.  &para; What nedith more declaracioun?  &para; Wher-for, whan the list to know how manye howres of the clokke ben passed, or any part of any of thise howris &thorn;at ben passed, &para; or elles how many howres or partie of howres ben to come, fro swich a tyme to swych a tyme, by day or by nyhte, &para; knowe the degree of thy sonne, &amp; ley thy label on it / turne thi Riet abowte ioyntly with thy label, &amp; with the point of it rekne in the bordure fro the sonne arise vn-to the same place ther thow desirest, by day as by nyhte / this conclusioun wol I declare in the laste chapitre of the [4] partie of this tretis so openly, &thorn;at [&thorn;er] shal lakke no worde &thorn;at nedith to the declaracioun.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>12. Special declarcioun of the howres of planetes.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Specialis declaracio de horis planetarum.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Vnderstond wel, &thorn;at euere-mo fro the arising of [the] sonne til it go to reste / the nader of the sonne shal shewe the howr of the planete / &amp; fro that tyme forward / al the nyht til the sonne arise / than shal the verrey degree of the sonne shewe the howr of the planete.  Ensample as thus.  &para; the xiij. day of March fil vp-on a saterday per auenture / &amp; at the arising of the sonne, I fond the secounde degree of aries sitting vp-on myn est Orisonte, al be it &thorn;at it was but lite; <MILESTONE
N="14b" UNIT="folio">than fond I the [2] degree of libra, nadir of my sonne, dessending on my west Orisonte, vp-on which west Orisonte euery day generally, at the sonne ariste, entrith the howr of any planete, after which planete the day berith his name; &para; &amp; endith in
<PB N="24">the nexte strik of the plate vnder the forseide west Orisonte / &amp; euere
as the sonne clymbith vppere &amp; vppere, so goth his nadir downere
&amp; downere, techyng by swych strikes the howres of planetes by ordre
as thei sitten in the heuene.  the first howr inequal of euery Satterd[a]y is to Saturne ; &para; &amp; the secounde to Iupiter; &para; the 3 to Mars ; the 4 to the sonne ; &para; the 5 to venus ; &para; the 6 to Mercurius; &para; the 7 to the mone ; &para; &amp; thanne agayn the 8 is to saturne ; 
&para; the 9 to Iupiter; &para; the 10 to Mars ; &para; the 11 to the sonne; 
&para; the 12 to venus ; &para; And now is my sonne gon to reste as for that setterday.  &para; Thanne shewyth the verrey degree of the sonne the howr
of Mercurie entryng vnder my west orisonte at eue; &para; &amp; next him
succedith the Mone ; &para; &amp; so forth by ordre, planete aftur planete,
in howr after howr, a1 the nyht longe til the sonne arise.  &para; now
risith the sonne &thorn;at Sonday be the morwe ; &para; &amp; the nadir of 
the sonne vp-on the west Orizonte shewith me the entring of the howre of the
forseide sonne.  &para; &amp; in this maner succedith planete vnder planete,
fro saturne vn-to the mone, &amp; fro the mone vp a-gayn to satourne,
howre after howre generaly.  &para; &amp; thus know[e] I this conclusioun.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="25"><MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>13. To knowe the altitude of the sonne in Middes of the
day, that is cleped the altitude Meridian.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum altitudinem solis in medio diei, que vocatur
altitudo meridiana.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the degree of the sonne vp-on the lyne Meridional, &amp;
rikene how many degrees of Almykanteras ben by-twyxe thyn est
Orisonte &amp; the degree of the sonne.  &para; &amp; tak ther thyn altitude
Meridian / this [is] to seyne, the heiest of the sonne as for that day.
&para; So maistow knowe in the same lyne, the heiest cours &thorn;at any
sterre fix clymbith by nyht ; &para; this is to seyn, &thorn;at w[h]an any 
sterre fix is passed the lyne Meridional, than by-gynnyth it to descende,
&amp; so doth the sonne.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thi
figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>14. To knowe the degree of the sonne by thy riet, for a maner
curiosite, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum gradum solis curiose.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Sek bysily with thi rewle the heiest of the sonne in Midde of
the day ; &para; turne thanne thyn Astrelabie, &amp; with a prikke of ynk
marke the nombre of &thorn;at same Altitude in the lyne Meridiona1.
turne thanne thy Ryet a-bowte til thow fynde a degree of thi
zodiak acording with the prikke, &para; this is to seyn, sittynge on the
prikke ; &para; &amp; in soth, thow shalt fynde but 2 degrees in a1 the
zodiak of that condicioun; &para; &amp; yit thilke 2 degrees ben in diuerse
signes; &para; than maistow lyhtly by the sesoun of the yere knowe the
signe in whiche &thorn;at is the sonne.   [&para; &amp; for the more 
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.]
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="26"><MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>15. To know which day is lik to wych day as of lengthe, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum quales dies in longitudine sunt similes.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Loke whiche degrees ben illik fer fro the heuedes of Cancer &amp;
Capricor&ntail; ; &amp; lok, whan the sonne is in any of thilke degrees,
than ben the dayes ilike of lengthe.  &para; this is to seyn, &thorn;at as long
is &thorn;at day in &thorn;at Monthe, as was swych a day in swich a month
&para; ther variet[h] but lite.  &para; Also yif &thorn;ow take 2 daies 
naturaly in the yer ilike fer fro eyther pointe of [the] equinoxial in the 
opposit parties, &para; than as long is the day artificial of &thorn;at on 
day / as is the nyht of &thorn;at othere, &amp; the contrarie. &para; &amp; 
for [the] more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>16.This chapitre is a Maner declaracioun to conclusiouns &thorn;at folwen.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Illud capitulum est quedam declaracio ad certas conclusiones sequentes.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Vnderstond wel &thorn;at thy zodiak is departid in 2 halfe cercles,
as fro the heued of capricorne vn-to the heued of Cancer / &amp;
agaynward fro the heued of cancer vn-to the heued of Capricorne.
&para; the heued of Capricorne is the lowest point, wher as the sonne
goth in wynter; &para; &amp; the heued of Cancer is the heiest point, in
whiche the sonne goth in somer.  &para; &amp; ther-for vnderstond wel, 
&thorn;at any two degrees &thorn;at ben ilike fer fro any of thise two heuedes
/ truste wel &thorn;at thilke two degrees ben of il[i]ke declinacioun, be it 
sowthward or northward ; &amp; the daies of hem ben ilike of lengthe, &amp; the
<PB N="27">nyhtes also ; &amp; the shadwes illke, &amp; the Altitudes ilike at Midday
for euere.  &para; &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>17. To knowe the verrey degree of any maner sterre straunge or vnstraunge 
after his longitude, thow he be indeterminat in thin astralabie; sothly to
the trowthe, thus he shal be knowe.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum verum gradum alicuius stelle aliene secundum
eius latitudinem (sic), quamvis sit indeterminata in astrolabio; veraciter 
isto modo.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Tak the altitude of this sterre whan he is on the Est side of
the lyne Meridional, as ney as thow maist gesse ; &para; &amp; tak an
assendent a-non riht by som maner sterre fix which &thorn;at &thorn;ow knowest
&para; &amp; for-get nat the altitude of the firste sterre, ne thyn assendent ;
4 &amp; whan &thorn;at this is don / espie diligently whan this same firste 
sterre passeth any-thing the sowth westward, and hath him a-non riht in the
same nowmbre of altitude on the west side of this lyne Meridional
&para; as he was kawht on the est side ; &amp; tak a newe assendent a-non riht by som Maner sterre fixe which &thorn;at thow knowest ; &amp; for-get nat
this secounde assendent. &para; and whan &thorn;at this is don, rikne thanne
how manye degrees ben by-twixe the firste assendent &amp; the seconde
assendent / &amp; rikne wel the Middel degree by-twyne bothe Assendentes,
<PB N="28"> &amp; set thilke Middel degree vp-on thin est Orisonte ; &para; &amp;
waite thanne what degre &thorn;at sit vp-on the line Meridional, &amp; tak ther
the verrey degre of the Ecliptik in which the sterre stondeth for
the tyme.  &para; For in the Ecliptik is the longitude of a celestial body
rekened, euene fro the heued of aries vn-to [the] ende of pisces.
&para; &amp; his latitude is Rikned after the quantite of [h]is declinacion,
north or sowth to-warde &thorn;e poles of this world / as thus. &para; yif it 
be of the sonne or of any fix sterre / rekene [h]is latitude or his declinacioun fro thu Equinoxial cercle; &para; &amp; yif it be of a planete, 
rekne than the quantite of [h]is latitude fro the Ecliptik lyne.  &para; Al 
be it so &thorn;at fro [the] Equinoxial may the declinacion or the latitude 
of any body celestial be rikned, after the site north or south, &amp; after the
quantite of [h]is declinacion. &para; &amp; riht so may the latitude or the 
declinacion of any body celestial, saue only of the sonne, after his site
north or south, &amp; after the quantite of his declinacioun, be rekned fro
the Ecliptik lyne ; &para; Fro which lyne alle planetes som tyme declinen
north or south, saue only the for-seide sonne. &para; &amp; for the more
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><PB N="29"><MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio">
<DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>18. To knowe the degrees of the longitudes of fixe sterres after &thorn;at 
they ben determinat in thin astralabie, yif so be &thorn;at they ben trewly 
set.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum gradus longitudinis de stellis fixis que determinantur in astrolabio, sicut in suis locis recte locentur.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the centre of the sterre vp-on the lyne Meridional, &amp; tak
kep of thi zodiak, &para; &amp; loke what degree of any signe &thorn;at sit 
on the same lyne Meridional at &thorn;at same tyme, &amp; tak the degree in 
which the sterre standith ; &para; &amp; with that same degree com[e]th 
&thorn;at same sterre vn-to that same lyne fro the Orisonte. &para; &amp; 
for more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>19. To knowe with which degree of the zodiak any sterre fixe in thin 
Astrelabie arisith vp-on the est Orisonte, Al-they [h]is dwellyng be in 
a-nother signe.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum cum quibus gradibus zodiaci que stella fyxa
in astrolabio ascendit super orizontem orientalem, quamuis
eius orizon (sic) sit in alio signo.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the Sentre of the sterre vp-on the est Orisonte, &para; &amp; loke what degre of any signe &thorn;at sit vp- on the same Orisonte at &thorn;at same
tyme.  &para; And vnderstond wel, &thorn;at with &thorn;at same degre arisith &thorn;at
same sterre ; and thys <MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio">merueyllous arising with a strange de-gree in another signe is by-cause &thorn;at the latitude of the sterre fix is either north or sowth fro the equinoxial.  &para; but sothly, the latitudes
<PB N="30">of planetes ben comu[n]ly rekned fro the Ecliptik, bi-cause &thorn;at non
of hem declinet[h] but fewe degrees owt fro the brede of the zodiak.
&para; &amp; tak god kep of this chapitre of arising of the celestial bodies ;
for truste wel, &thorn;at neyther mone ne sterre as in owre Embelif
orisonte arisith with &thorn;at same degree of his longitude, saue in O cas;
&para; &amp; that is, whan they haue no latitude fro the Ecliptik lyne. but
natheles som tyme is eueriche of thes planetes vnder the same lyne.
&para; &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>20.To knowe the declinacioun of any degree in the zodiak fro
the equinoxial cercle, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum declinacionem alicuius gradus [in] zodiaco
[a] circulo equinoctiali.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the degree of any signe vp-on the lyne Meridional, &amp;
rikne [h]is altitude in Almykanteras fro the Est Orizonte vp to the
same degree set in the forseide lyne, &amp; set ther a prikke. &para; turne vp
thanne thy Riet, and set the heued of aries or libra in the same
Meridional lyne, &amp; set ther a-nother prikke. &para; &amp; whan &thorn;at 
this is don, considere the <MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio">Altitudes of hem bothe ; for sothly the
difference of thilke altitudes is the declinacion of thilke degre fro
the equinoxial. &para; &amp; yif so be &thorn;at thilke degree be northward 
fro the equinoxial, than is his declinacion north ; &para; yif it be sowthward,
than is it sowth. &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="31">
<HEAD>21. To knowe for what latitude in any regioun the Almikanteras of any 
table ben compowned.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum pro qua latitudine in aliqua regione almicantre tabule 
mee sunt composite.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Rikne how manie degrees of Almikanteras in the Meridional
lyne be fro the cercle equinoxial vn-to the senyth ; &para; Or elles fro the
pool artik vn-to the north Orisonte; &amp; for so gret a latitude or for so
smal a latitude is the table compowned. &para; &amp; for more declaracion,
lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>22. To knowe in special the latitude of owre countray, I mene after the 
latitude of Oxenford, &amp; the heyhte of owre pol.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum specialiter latitudinem nostri centri (sic),
scilicet latitudinem Oxonie, et altitudinem poli nostri.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Vnderstond wel, &thorn;at as fer is the heued of aries or libra in the
equinoxial from owre orisonte as is the cenyth fro the pole artik ;
&para; &amp; as hey [is] the pol Artik fro the Orisonte as the Equinoxial is
fer fro the senyth.  &para; I proue it thus by the latitude of Oxenford /
vnderstond wel, &thorn;at the heyhte of owre pool Artik fro owre north
Orisonte is 51 degrees &amp; 50 Minutes; than is the cenyth from owre
pool Artik 38 degrees &amp; l0 Minutes; than is the equinoxial from
owre senyth 51 degrees &amp; 50 Minutes; &para; than is owre south Orisonte
from owre equinoxial 38 degrees &amp; l0 Minutes.  &para; vnderstond wel
<PB N="32">this Reknyng.  &para; Also for-get nat &thorn;at the cenyth is 90 degrees of
heyhte fro the Orisonte, &amp; owre equinoxial is 90 degrees from owre
pool Artik.  &para; Also this shorte rewle is soth, &thorn;at the latitude of
any place in a regioun is the distance fro the senyth vnto the Equinoxial. &para; &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here &thorn;i figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>23. To proue euidently the latitude of any place in a Regioun, by the 
preue of the heyhte of the pol Artik in &thorn;at same place.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad probandum euidenter latitudinem alicuius loci in aliqua
regione, per probacionem altitudinis de polo artico in eodem loco.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>In some wynters nyht, whan the firmament is clere &amp; thikke-
sterred / waite a tyme til &thorn;at any sterre fix sit lyne-riht perpendiculer ouer <MILESTONE
N="18b" UNIT="folio">the pol Artik, &amp; clepe &thorn;at sterre A. &para; &amp; wayte 
a-nother sterre &thorn;at sit lyne-riht vnder A, &amp; vnder the pol / &amp; 
clepe &thorn;at sterre F. And vnderstond wel, &thorn;at F is nat consideret but only [to] declare &thorn;at A sit euene ouere the pool.  &para; tak thanne a-non riht the 
altitude of A from the Orisonte / &amp; forget it nat.  &para; Lat A &amp; 
F go farwel til agayns the dawenyng a gret while / &amp; come thanne agayn 
&amp; Abid til &thorn;at A is euene vnder the pol &amp; vnder F ; &para; for 
sothly, than wole F sit ouer the pool / &amp; A wol sit vnder the pool. &para;
tak than eft-sones the altitude of A from the Orisonte &para; &amp; note as 
wel [h]is secounde altitude as his furste Altitude / &amp; whan &thorn;at this
is don, &para; rikne how manye degrees &thorn;at the firste altitude of A excedith his
seconde altitude, &para; &amp; tak half thilke porcioun &thorn;at is excedit, 
&amp; adde it to his seconde altitude ; &para; &amp; tak ther the eleuacioun of thi pool,
&amp; eke the latitude of thy regioun ; &para; for thise two ben of a nombre ;
&para; this is to seyn, as many degrees as thy pool is eleuat / so michel
<PB N="33">is the latitude of the Regioun.  &para; Ensample as thus:  par auenture
the altitude of A in the euenyng is 56 degrees of heyte than wol 
his seconde altitude or the dawyng be 48 / &thorn;at is [8] lasse than 56,
&thorn;at was his furste altitude at euen. &para; take thanne the of 8 / &amp;
adde it to 48, &thorn;at was [h]is seconde altitude, and [than] hastow 52.
&para; now hastow the heyhte of thy pol and the latitude of the regioun
&para; but vnderstond wel &thorn;at to proue this conclusioun &amp; many a-nother fair conclusioun, thow most haue a plomet hanging on a lyne heyer
than thin heued on a perche &para; &amp; thilke lyne mot hange euene 
perpendiculer by-twixe the pool &amp; thin eye / &amp; thanne shal-tow sen 
yif A sitte euene ouer the pool &amp; ouer F at euene / &amp; also yif F sitte euene
ouer the pool &amp; ouer A or day. &para; &amp; for more declaracion, lo here
thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>24. Another conclusioun to proue the heyhte of the pool Artik fro the 
orisonte.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Alia conclusio ad probandum altitudinem de polo artico ab orizonte.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Tak any sterre fixe &thorn;at neuere dissendith vnder the Orisonte in
thilke regioun, &amp; considere his heiest altitude &amp; his lowest Altitude
fro the Orisonte ; &para; &amp; make a nombre of bothe thise altitudes ; tak
thanne &amp; abate half &thorn;at nombre, &amp; tak &thorn;er the eleuacioun of the pol Artik in &thorn;at same Regioun / &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here thi
figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="34">
<HEAD>25. A-nother conclusioun to proue the latitude of the Regioun, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Alia conclusio ad probandum latitudinem regionis.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Vnderstond wel &thorn;at the latitude of any place in A Regioun is
verreyly the space by-twixe the senythe of hem &thorn;at dwellen there &amp;
[the] equinoxial cerkle, north or sowthe, takyng the mesure in the
Meridional lyne, as shewith in the Almykanteras of thin Astrelabie.
&para; &amp; thilke space is as moche as the pool artik is hey in the same
place fro the Orisonte.  &para; And than is the depressioun of the pol
antartik, &thorn;at is to seyn, than is the pol antartik by-nethe the
Orisonte the same quantite of space, neither mor ne lasse. thanne,
yif thow desire to knowe this latitude of the Regioun, tak the altitude of 
the sonne in the Middel of the day, whan the sonne is in the
heuedes of aries or of libra / for thanne Moeuyth the sonne in the
lyne equinoxial ; &para; &amp; abate the nombre of that same sonnes Altitude
owt of 90, &amp; thanne is the remenaunt <MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio">of the noumbre &thorn;at leuyth the latitude of the Regioun, as thus : I suppose that the sonne
is thilke day at noon 38 degrees And l0 minutes of heyhte.  Abate
thanne thees degrees And minutes owt of 90 ; so leueth there 51
degrees and 50 minutes, the latitude.  &para; I sey nat this but for ensample ; for wel I wot the latitude of Oxenforde is certein minutes
lasse, as y myght proue.  &para; Now yif so be &thorn;at the semith to long a
tarienge, to abide til &thorn;at [&thorn;e] sonne be in the heuedes of aries 
or of libra, thanne whaite whan the sonne is in any other degree of the
zodiak, &amp; considere the degree of [h]is declinacion fro the equinoxial
lyne ; &para; &amp; yif it so be &thorn;at the sonnes declinacion be northward
fro the equinoxial, abate thanne fro the sonnes altitude at noon the nombre
<PB N="35">of his declinacion, &para; &amp; thanne hastow the heyhte of the heuedes of
aries &amp; libra ; as thus / My sonne is, par Auenture, in &thorn;e firste
degre of leoun, 58 degrees and 10 Minutes of heyhte at noon / &amp;
his declinacion is almost 20 degrees northward fro the equinoxial ;
abate thanne thilke 20 degrees of declinacion owt of the altitude at
noon, than leueth the 38 degrees and odde Minutes ; lo ther the
heued of aries or libra, &amp; thin equinoxial in that Regioun.  &para; Also
yif so be &thorn;at the sonnes declinacioun be sowthward fro the Equinoxial, 
&para; Adde thanne thilke declinacion to the altitude of the sonne
at noon / and tak ther the heuedes of aries &amp; libra &amp; thin Equinoxial.
&para; abate thanne the heyhte of the Equinoxial owt of 90 degrees,
&amp; thanne leuyth there &thorn;e distans of the pole, 51 degrees &amp; 50
Minutes, of that regioun fro the Equinoxial.  &para; Or elles yif the
lest, take the haiest altitude fro the equinoxial of any sterre fix that
thow knowest, &amp; tak his nethere elongacioun lengthing fro the same
equinoxial lyne, &amp; wirke in the maner forseid. &para; &amp; for more 
declaracion, lo here thi figure.    
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>26. Declaracioun of the assensioun of signes, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Declaracio de ascensione signorum.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>The excellence of the spere solide, amonges other noble conclusiouns, shewyth Manifeste the diuerse assenciouns of signes in
diuerse places, as wel in the rihte cercle as in the Embelif cercle.
&para; thise Auctours writen &thorn;at thilke signe is clept of riht 
Ascensioun, with which more part of the cercle Equinoxial &amp; lasse part of the
zodiak ascendith / &amp; thilke signe assendith Embelif, with whiche
lasse part of the Equinoxial and more part of the zodiak assendith.
<PB N="36">[Ferther ouer they seyn, that in thilke cuntrey where as the senith
of hem that dwellen there is in the equinoxial lyne and her orisonte
passyng by the poles of this worlde, thilke folke han this right cercle
and the right orisonte;] &para; &amp; euere mo the Arch of the day &amp; 
the arch of the nyht is ther ylike long, &amp; the sonne twyes euery yer passinge
thorow the cenyth of her heued; &amp; 2 someres &amp; 2 wynteres in a yer
han this forseide poeple.  &para; And the Almykanteras in her Astrolabies
ben streyhte as a lyne / so as shewyth in this figure.  &para; The vtilite to
knowe the Assenciouns in the rihte cercle is this / truste wel &thorn;at by
mediacioun of thilke assenciouns thise Astrologiens by hir tables &amp;
<PB N="37">hir instrumentz knowen verreyly the Assencioun of euery degree &amp;
Mynut in al the zodiak, as shal be shewyd.  &para; And nota, &thorn;at this
forseid rihte orisonte, &thorn;at is clepid <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">orison rectum</FOREIGN> / diuideth the equinoxial in-to riht Angles ; &amp; the embelif orisonte, wher as the
pol is enhawsed vp-on the orisonte, ouerkeruyth the equinoxial in
Embelif Angles, as shewith in the figure. &para; &amp; for the more 
declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>27.This is the conclusioun to knowe the Assenciouns of signes in the riht cercle, &thorn;at is, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">circulus directus, &amp;c.</FOREIGN></HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum ascenciones signorum in recto circulo, qui vocatur 
circulus directus.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"><P>Set the heued of what signe the liste to knowe his
Assending in the riht cercle / vp-on [the] lyne Meridional, &para; &amp; waite
wher thin Almury towchiet[h] the bordure, &amp; set ther a prikke/ turne
thanne thy riet westward til &thorn;at the ende of the forseide signe sitte
vp-on the Meridional lyne / &amp; eft-sones waite wher thin almury
towchith the bordure, &amp; set ther Another prikke.  Rikne thanne the
nombre of degrees in the bordure by-twyxe bothe prikkes, &para; &amp; tak
the Assencioun of the signe in the riht cercle.  And thus maistow
wyrke with euery porcioun of thy zodiak, &amp;c. &para; &amp; for the more
declaracioun, lo her thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>28.To knowe the assencions of signes in the Embelif cercle in euery 
regioun, I Mene, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">in circulo obliquo.</FOREIGN></HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum ascenciones signorum in recto (sic!) circulo in omni 
regione, hoc est, in circulo obliquo.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Set the heued of the signe which as the list to knowe his Ascensioun
<PB N="38"> vp-on the est Orisonte, &para; &amp; waite wher thyn Almury towchith 
the bordure, &amp; [set] ther a prikke.  &para; turne thanne thy riet
vpward til &thorn;at the ende of the same signe sitte vp-on the Est Orisonte 
/ and waite eft-sones wher as thin almury towcheth the
bordure, &amp; set ther a-nother prikke.  &para; Rikne thanne the nowmbre
of degrees in the bordure by-twyxe bothe prikkes, &amp; tak ther the
Assencioun of the signe in the Embelif cercle.  &para; &amp; vnderstond wel,
&thorn;at alle signes in thy zodiak fro the heued of aries vnto the ende
of virgo ben cleped signes of the north fro the Equinox[i]al, &para; &amp;
the[se] signes arisen by-twyxe the verrey est &amp; the verrey north in
owre Orisonte generaly for euere ; &amp; alle signes fro the heued of
libra vn-to &thorn;e ende of pisces ben cleped signes of the sowth fro  
<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio">
the Equinoxial ; &para; &amp; thise signes arisen euer-mo by-twyxe the
verrey est &amp; the verrey sowth in owre orisonte.  &para; Also euery signe
by-twixe the heued of capricorne vn-to the ende of geminis ariseth
on owre Orisonte in lasse than 2 howres equales; &para; &amp; thise same
signes, fro the heued of capricorne vn-to the ende of geminis, ben
cleped tortuos signes or kroked signes / for they arisen embelif on
oure Orisonte; &para; &amp; thise crokede signes ben obedient to the signes
&thorn;at ben of riht Assencioun.  &para; The signes of riht assencioun ben
fro the heued of cancer to &thorn;e [ende] of sagittare; &para; &amp; thise 
signes arisen more vpriht, &amp; they ben called eke souereyn signes ; &para; &amp;
euerich of hem ariseth in mor space than in to howres.  &para; Of which
<PB N="39">signes gemini obeieth to Cancer, &para; &amp; taurus to leo / Aries to virgo /
pisces to libra, &para; Aquarius to Scorpioun, and Capricorne to Sagittare.
&para; &amp; thus euermo 2 signes that ben illike fer fro the heued of
capricorne / obeien euerich of hem til other.  &para; &amp; for more 
declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>29.To knowe Iustly the 4 quarters of the world, as est, west,
north, &amp; sowth.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum euidenter quatuor partes mundi, scilicet,
orientem, austrum, aquilonem, &amp; occidentem.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Take the altitude of thy sonne whan the list / &amp; note wel the
quarter of the world in which the sonne is for the tyme by the
Azymutz.  &para; turne thanne thin Astrolabie / &amp; set the degree of the
sonne in the Almykanteras of his altitude on thilke side &thorn;at the
sonne stant / as is the manere in takyng of howres ; &para; &amp; ley thy
label on the degree of the sonne, And rikene how many degres of the
bordure ben by-twixe the lyne Meridional &amp; the point of thy
label; &amp; note wel &thorn;at nowmbre.  &para; <MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio">Turne thanne a-gayn thyn Astralabie, &amp; set the point of thy gret Rewle ther thow takest
thyne Altitudes / vp-on as many degrees in his bordure fro his Meridional 
as was the point of thy label fro the lyne Meridional on the
wombe-side.  &para; tak thanne thyn Astrolabie with bothe handes sadly
&amp; slely, &amp; lat the sonne shyne thorow bothe holes of thy rewle; 
&para; &amp; sleyly in thilke shynynge lat thyn Astrelabie kowch adown euene vp-
on a smothe grond, &amp; thanne wol the verrey lyne Merydional of thyn
<PB N="40">Astrolabie lye euene sowth, &amp; the est lyne wole lie est, &amp; the west
lyne west, &amp; north lyne north, so &thorn;at thow werke softly &amp; 
avisely in the cowchyng ; &amp; thus hastow the 4 quarters of the firmament.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>30. To knowe the Altitude of planetes fro the wey of the sonne,
whether so they be north or sowth fro the forseide wey.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum altitudinem planetarum a cursu solis, utrum
sint in parte australi vel boreali a cursu supra dicto.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Lok whan &thorn;at a planete is in the lyne Meridional, yif 
&thorn;at hir altitude be of the same heyhte &thorn;at is the degree of the sonne for 
&thorn;at day, &amp; than is the planete in the verrey wey of the sonne, &para; &amp; 
hath no latitude.  &para; &amp; yif the altitude of the planete be heyere than the
degree of the sonne, &thorn;an is the planete north fro the wey of the
sonne swych a quantite of latitude as [shewith] by thyn Almykanteras.  
&amp; &yogh;if the altitude of the planete be lasse than the degree
of the sonne / thanne <MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="folio">is the planete sowth fro the wey of
the sonne swich a quantite of latitude as [shewith] by thin almykanteras ; 
&para; This is to seyn, fro the wey wher as the sonne wente thilke
day / but nat from the wey of the sonne in euery place of the zodiak.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>31. To knowe the senyth of the arysing of the sonne, this is to
seyn, the partie of the Orisonte in which &thorn;at the sonne
arisith.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum signum de ortu solis, scilicet, illam partem
orientis in qua oritur sol.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Thow most first considere &thorn;at the sonne ariseth nat al-wey
verrey est, but some tyme by north the est, and som tyme by sowthe
<PB N="41">the est / Sothly the sonne ariseth neuer-mo verrey est in owere
Orisonte, &para; but he be in the heued of aries or libra. now is thin
Orisonte departed in 24 parties by thi azymutz, in significacion of 24
partiez of the world; al be it so &thorn;at shipmen rikne thilke partiez in
32 / thanne is ther no more but waite in which azymut &thorn;at thi sonne
entreth at [h]is arisyng / &amp; take ther the senyth of the arising of the
sonne.  &para; the manere of the deuisioun of thin Astralabie is this / I
Mene as in this cas.  &para; First is it deuided in 4 plages principalx
with the lyne &thorn;at goth from est to west, &para; &amp; than with 
a-nother lyne &thorn;at goth fro so[w]th to north.  &para; than is it deuided in smale 
partiez of Azymutz, as est, and est by sowthe, whereas is the firste Azimut
aboue the est lyne ; &para; &amp; so forth fro partie to partie / til 
&thorn;at thow come agayn vn-to the est lyne / thus maistow vnderstond also the
senyth of any sterre, in which partie he riseth, &amp;c. &para; &amp; for 
the more declaracion, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>32. To knowe in which partie of the firmament is the
coniunccioun.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum in qua parte firmamenti sunt coniuncciones
solis &amp; lune.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Considere the tyme of the coniuncc[i]on by thy kalender / as
thus ; lok how many howres thilke coniunccion is fro the Midday of
<PB N="42">the day precedent, as shewith by the canoun of thi kalender; &para; rikne
thanne thilke nombre of howres in the bordure of thyn Astralabie /
as thow art wont to do in knowyng of the howres of the day or of
the nyht; &para; &amp; ley thy label ouer the degree of the sonne; &para; &amp;
thanne wol the point of thy label sitte vp-on the hour of the con-
iunccion.  &para; loke thanne in which Azymut the degree of thy sonne
sittith, &amp; in that partie of the firmament is the coniunccioun.  &para; 
&amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here thy figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>33. To knowe the senyth of the Altitude of the sonne, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum signa de altitudine solis.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>This is no mor to seyn but any tyme of the day tak the altitude
of the sonne, &amp; by the Azymut in which he stondith, &para; Maistou
sen in which partie of the firmament he is &para; &amp; [in] the same wyse
maistou sen, by the nyht, of any sterre, wheither the sterre sitte est
or west or north, or any partie by-twene, aftur the name of the
Azimut in which is the sterre.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo
here the figure.</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>34. To knowe sothly the degree of the longitude of the mone,
or of any planete &thorn;at hath no latitude for the tyme fro the
Ecliptik lyne.</HEAD><PB N="43"><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad cognoscendum veraciter gradum de longitudine lune, vel
alicuius planete qui non habet longitudinem pro tempore
causante (sic) linea ecliptica.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Tak the altitude of the mone, &amp; rikne thin altitude vp among
thyne Almykanteras on which side that the Mone stande, &amp; set there
a prikke. &para; Tak thenne anon riht, vp-on the mones side, the Altitude
of any sterre fix which &thorn;at thow knowest, &amp; set his Centre vp-on his
altitude Among thin Almykanteras ther the sterre is fownde.
&para; Waite thanne which degree of the zodiak [towchith] the prikke of
the altitude of the mone, &amp; tak ther the degree in which the mone
standith.  &para; this conclusioun is verrey soth, yif the sterres in thin
Astrolabie stonden aftur <MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio">the trowthe ; of comune, tretis of Astralabie ne make non excepcioun wheyth[er] the mone haue latitude, or non / ne on wheither side of the mone the Altitude of the
sterre fix be taken.  &para; And nota, &thorn;at yif the Mone [shewe] 
himself by liht of day, than maistow wyrke this same conclusioun by the sonne,
as wel as by the fix sterre.  &para; &amp; for the more declaracioun, lo here
thy figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>35. This is the workinge of the conclusioun, to knowe yif &thorn;at any planete be directe or retrograde.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Hec conclusio operatur ad cognoscendum si aliqua planeta sit directa uel retrograda.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Tak the altitude of any sterre &thorn;at is cleped a planete, &para; &amp; note
it wel.  &para; &amp; tak ek anon the altitude of any sterre fix that thow
<PB N="44">knowest, &amp; note it wel also.  &para; Come thanne agayn the thridde or
the ferthe nyht next folwyng ; for thanne shaltow aperceyue wel the
Moeuyng of a planete, wheither so he Moeue forthward or bakward.
&para; Awaite wel thanne w[h]an &thorn;at thi sterre fix is in the same 
altitude &thorn;at she was w[h]an thow toke hir firste altitude ; &para; and tak than 
eftsones the Altitude of the forseide planete, &amp; note it wel.  &para; for 
trust wel, yif so be &thorn;at the planete be on the riht side of the 
Meridional lyne, so &thorn;at his seconde altitude be lasse than [h]is 
firste altitude was, thanne is the planete directe.  &para; And yif he be on the west side in
that condicion / thanne is he retrograd.  &para; And yif so be &thorn;at this
planete be vp-on the Est side whan [h]is altitude is <MILESTONE
N="24" UNIT="folio">taken, so &thorn;at his secounde altitude be more than [h]is firste altitude, thanne is
he retrograde, &amp; yif he be on the west side, than is he directe.  &para; 
but the contrarie of this parties is of the cours of the Moone ; for
[sothly] the Moone Moeuyth the contrarie from othere planetes as in
hire Episicle, but in non other manere.  &para; &amp; for the more 
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53">
<HEAD>36. The conclusiouns of equaciouns of howses, after the astralabie, &amp;c.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Conclusio de equacione domorum.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Set the by-gynnyng of the degree &thorn;at assendith vp-on the ende of
the 8 howre inequal ; thanne wol the by-gynnyng of the 2 hows
sitte vp-on the lyne of Midnyht.  &para; rem[e]ue thanne the degree &thorn;at
assendith, &amp; set him on the ende of the 10 howr inequal; &amp; thanne
<PB N="45">wol the by-gynnyng of the 3 howis sitte vp-on the Midnyht lyne.
&para; bryng vp agayn the same degree &thorn;at assendith first / &amp; 
set him vp-on the Orisonte / &amp; thanne wol the be-gynnyng of the 4 howys
sitte vp-on the lyne of Midnyht.  &para; tak thanne the nadir of the
degree &thorn;at first Assendith / &amp; set him on the ende of the 2 howre
inequal / &amp; thanne wol the by-gynnyng of the 5 howys sitte vp-on
the lyne of Midnyth ; set thanne the nadir of the assendent on the
ende of the 4 howre, &thorn;an wol the bygynnyng of the 6 house sitte on
the Midnyht lyne.  &para; &thorn;e bygynnyng of the 7 hows is nadir of the
Assendent / &amp; the bygynnyng of the 8 hows is nadir of the 2; &amp; &thorn;e
by-gynnyng of the 9 hous is nadir of the 3 ; &amp; &thorn;e by-gynnyng of 
&thorn;e 10 hows is the nadir of the 4 ; &amp; &thorn;e bygynnyng of the 11 howys is
nader of the 5 ; &amp; the bygynnyng of the 12 hows is nadir of the 6.
&para; &amp; for the more declaracion, lo here the figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>37. A-nother manere of equaciouns of howses by the Astrelabie.</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[De aliqua forma equacionis domorum secundum astrolabium.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Tak thin assendent, &amp; thanne hastow thi 4 Angles; for wel
thow wost &thorn;at the opposit of thin assendent, &thorn;at is to seyn, thy
by-gynnyng of the 7 howis, sit vp-on the west orizonte ; &para; &amp; the
bygynnyng of the 10 howis sit vp-on the lyne Meridional ; &para; &amp; his
opposit vp- on the lyne of Mydnyht.  &para; Thanne ley thi label ouer
<PB N="46">the degree &thorn;at assendet[h] / &amp; rekne fro the point of thy label alle
the degrees in the bordure, til thow come to the Meridional lyne / &amp;
departe alle thilke degrees in 3 euene parties, &amp; take the euene
equacion of 3 ; for ley thy label ouer euerich of 3 parties, &amp; [than]
maistow se by thy label in which degree of the zodiak [is] the by-
gynnyng of euerich of thise same howses fro the assendent / &thorn;at is to
seyn, the begynyng of the [12] howse nex[t] aboue thin assendent /
And [thanne] the begynnyng of the 11 howse, &amp; thanne the 10 vp-on the Meridional lyne / as I first seide.  &para; The same wyse wyrke
thow fro the assendent down to the lyne of Mydnyht / &amp; thanne
thus hastow other 3 howses, &thorn;at is to seyn, the bygynnyng of the 2
&amp; the 3 And the 4 howses ; thanne is [the] nader of thise 3 howsez
the by-gynnyng of the 3 howses &thorn;at folwen.  &para; &amp; for the more 
declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>38. To fynde the lyne Merydional to dwelle fix in any
certein place.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Ad inueniendum lineam meridionalem per subtiles operaciones.]</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Tak a rond plate of metal, for [warpyng] the brodere the bettre ;
&para; &amp; make ther-vpon [a] Iust compas, a lite with-in the bordure / &amp;
ley this ronde plate vp-on an euene grond or on a[n] euene ston or on
a[n] euene stok fix in the gronde / &amp; ley it euen bi a leuel &para; 
&amp; in centre of the compas stike an euene pyn or a whir vp-riht / the smallere &thorn;e
betere &para; set thy pyn by a plom-rewle euene vpryht &para; &amp; let this 
pyn be no lengere than a quarter of the diametre of thi compas, fro the
centre.  &para; &amp; waite bisily aboute 10 or 11 of the clokke, &amp; whan the
<PB N="47">sonne shynyth, whan the shadwe of the pyn entreth any-thyng
with-in the cercle of thi plate an her-mele, &para; &amp; mark ther a prikke
with inke.  Abide thanne stille waityng on the sonne aftur 1 of the
clokke, til that the schadwe of the wyr or of the pyn passe ony-thyng
owt of the cercle of the compas, be it neuer so lite / &amp; set ther
a-nother prikke of ynke.  &para; take than a compas, and mesure euene
the Middel by-twixe bothe prikkes, &amp; set &thorn;er a prikke.  &para; take
thanne a rewle / &amp; draw a strike, euene alyne fro the pyn vn-to the
Middel prikke; &para; &amp; tak ther thy lyne Meridional for euere-mo, as in
that same place.  &para; &amp; yif thow drawe a cros-lyne ouer-thwart the
compas Iustly ouer the lyne Meridional, than hastow est and west
&amp; sowth / &amp;, par consequence, than the nader of the sowth lyne is
the north lyne.  &para; &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1
TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD>39. Descripcion of the Meridional lyne, of longitudes, &amp;
latitudes of Citees and townes from on to a-no[t]her of clymatz.</HEAD><P>This lyne Meridional ys but a Maner descripcion [of lyne]
ymagined, that passeth vpon the pooles of &thorn;is world And by the
cenyth of owre heued / And hit is [ycleped the] lyne Meridional / for
in what place &thorn;at any maner man [ys at] any tyme of the yer / whan
that the sonne [by moeuyng] of the firmament cometh to his verrey
[meridian] place , than is hit verrey Midday, &thorn;at we clepen owre
noon, &para; As to thilke man ; &para; And therfore ys it clepid &thorn;e lyne of
<PB N="48">Midday.  &para; And nota, for euermo, of [2 citees] or of 2 Townes, of
whiche &thorn;at o town aprochith [more] towarde the Est &thorn;an doth &thorn;at
other town, &para; Truste wel that thylke townes han diuerse Meridians.
&para; Nota also, that the Arch of the Equinoxial that is [conteyned] or
bownded by-twyxe the 2 Meridians ys cleped &thorn;e longitude of the
town.  &para; And [yf] so be &thorn;at two townes haue illike Meridian, or on
Meridian, &para; Than is the distance of hem bothe ylike fer fro the Est /
&amp; the contrarie.  And in this Manere they chaunge nat her Meridian,
&para; But sothly they chaungen here Almikanteras, For the enhausyng
of the pool and the distance of the sonne.  &para; The longitude of a
clymat ys a lyne ymagined fro Est to west, illike distant by-twene
them alle.  &para; &thorn;e latitude of a climat is a lyne ymagined from north
to south &thorn;e space of the erthe, fro the byginnyng <MILESTONE
N="26" UNIT="folio">of the firste clymat vnto to the verrey ende of the [same] climat, euene directe
agayns [&thorn;e poole Artik.]  &para; Thus seyn some Auctours / And somme
of hem seyn &thorn;at yif men clepen &thorn;e latitude, thay mene the arch 
meridian &thorn;at is contiened or [inter]cept by-twixe the cenyth and the
eqninoxial.  Thanne sey &thorn;ey that the distaunce fro the equinoxial
vnto &thorn;e ende of a clymat, euene agayns &thorn;e pool artyk, ys the 
latitude of a climat for sothe.  &para; &amp; for more declaracioun, lo here thi figure.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="section" ANA="MS.Dd.3.53"><PB N="49">
<HEAD>40.To knowe with which degree of the zodiak &thorn;at any planete
Assendith on the Orisonte, wheyther so that his latitude be north or sowth.</HEAD><P>&para; Knowe be thin almenak the degree of the Ecliptik of any
signe in which &thorn;at the planete is rekned for to be / &amp; that is cleped
the degree of his longitude; &amp; knowe Also the degree of his latitude fro the Ecliptik, north or sowth.  &para; And by this samples
folwynge in special / maistow wyrke for [sothe] in euery signe of the
zodiak.  the degree of [longitude] par auenture, of venus or of
another planete was 6 of Capricorne, &amp; the latitude of him was
northward 2 degrees fro the Ecliptik lyne.  I tok a subtil compas,
&amp; cleped &thorn;at on poynt of my compas A, &amp; &thorn;at other poynt F.
&para; Than [tok] I the point of A, &amp; set it in [the] Ecliptik line 
euene in my zodiak, in the degree of the longitude of venus / &thorn;at is to seyn, in
the 6 degree of Capricorne &para; &amp; thanne set I the point of F vpward
in the same <MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio">signe, bycause &thorn;at the latitude was north, vpon  the latitude of venus, that is to seyn, in the 6 degree fro the heued of capricorne; &amp; thus hauy 2 degrees by-twixe my to prikkes; than leide I down softely my compas, &para; &amp; sette the degree of the 
longitude vp-on the Orisonte / tho tok I &amp; wexede my label in Maner of
a peyre tables to resceyue distynctly the prikkes of my compas.
&para; Tho tok I this forseide label, &amp; leide it fix ouer the degree of my
longitude / tho tok I vp my compas, &para; &amp; sette the point of A in the
wex on my label, as euene as y kowde gesse ouer the Ecliptik lyne,
in the ende of [the] longitude / &amp; sette the point of F endlang in my
label vp-on the space of the latitude, inwarde &amp; ouer the zodiak, that
<PB N="50">is to seyn, north-ward fro the Ecliptik // than leide I down my compas &amp; 
lokede wel in the wey vpon the prikke of A &amp; of F; tho
turned I my Riet til &thorn;at the prikke of F sat vp-on the Orisonte /
than saw I wel &thorn;at the body of venus, in hir latitude of [2] degrees
septentrionalis, assendid, in the ende of the 6 degree, in the heued
of capricorne.  &para; And nota, &thorn;at in the same maner maistow wyrke
with any latitude septentrional [in alle] signes ; but sothly the
latitude Meridional of a planete in Capricorne may not be take, by
cause of the litel space by-twixe the Ecliptik / &amp; the bordure of the
Astrelabie; but sothly, in alle other [signes] it May.
</P><MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio"><P>&para; Also the degree, par auenture, of Iuppiter or of a-nother
planete, was in the furst degree of pisces in longitude / &amp; his latitude was 3 degrees Meridional; tho tok I the point of A / &amp; set it
in the firste degree of pisces on the Ecliptik / &amp; thanne set I the
point of F downward in the same signe, by cause &thorn;at the latitude was
sowth 3 degrees / &thorn;at is to sey&nmacr;, fro the heued of pisces / &amp; 
thus hauy 3 degrees by-twixe bothe prikkes ; thanne sette I the degree of the
longitude vp-on the Orisonte; tho tok I my label / &amp; leide it fix vp-on the degree of the longitude; tho sette I the point of A on my
label, euene ouer the Ecliptik lyne in the ende euene of the degree of
the longitude / &amp; set the point of [F endlang] in my label the space
[of] 3 [degrees] of the latitude fro the zodiak, this is to seyn,
sowthward fro the Ecliptik, toward the bordure; and turned my
<PB N="51">Riet [til] the prikke of F sat vp-on the Orisonte; thanne [saw] I wel
&thorn;at the body of Iuppiter, in his latitude of 3 degrees Meridional,
ascendit with 14 degrees of pisces <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">in horoscopo</FOREIGN> / &amp; in this Maner maistow wyrke with any latitude Meridional, as I first seide, saue in
Capricorne / And yif thow wolt pleie this craft with the arisyng of
the Mone, loke thow rekne wel her cours howre by howre; for she ne
dwellith nat in a degree of [hire] longitude but [a] litel while, as thow
wel knowest / but natheles, yif thow rekne hir verreye Moeuyng by
thy tables howre after howre&mdash;&mdash;[&thorn;ou shalt do wel ynow.</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Explicit tractatus de Conclusionibus Astrolabii compilatus per
Galfridum Chauciers ad Filium suum Lodewicum scolarem tunc
temporis Oxonie ac sub tutela illius nobilissimi Philosophi
Magistri N. Strode, &amp;c.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV1>
<DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section"><PB N="52">
<HEAD>41. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra Recta.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&YOGH;if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou wylt werke be <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">vmbra <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="folio">recta</FOREIGN>, &amp; &thorn;ou may come to &thorn;e bas of &thorn;e towre, in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou schalt werke.  Tak &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e tour be bo&thorn;e holes, so &thorn;at &thorn;i rewle ligge euyn in a poynt.  Ensample as &thorn;us : y see hym &thorn;orw at &thorn;e poynt of 4; &thorn;an mete y &thorn;e space be-twen me &amp; &thorn;e tour, &amp; y fynde yt 20 feet; &thorn;an be-holde y how 4 ys to 12, ri&yogh;t so is the space be[-twen] &thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e tour to &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e tour.  [For] 4 is &thorn;e [&thorn;]ridde 
part of 12, so is &thorn;e space be-twen &thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e tour &thorn;e &thorn;ridde part of &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e tour; &thorn;an &thorn;ries 20 feet ys &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e tour, wi&thorn; addyng of &thorn;yn owne persone to &thorn;yn eye; &amp; &thorn;is rewle is so general in <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">vmbra recta</FOREIGN>, fro &thorn;e poyn[t] of oon to 12.  And &yogh;if &thorn;i rewle falle vppon 5, &thorn;an is 5
12-partyes of &thorn;e hey&yogh;t &thorn;e space be-twen &thorn;e &amp; 
&thorn;e towre; wy&thorn; addyng of &thorn;yn owne hey&yogh;th.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>42. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra Versa.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Ano&thorn;er maner of werkynge, be <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">vmbra versa</FOREIGN>. &YOGH;if so be &thorn;at  &thorn;ou may nat come to &thorn;e bas of &thorn;e tour, y [see] hym  &thorn;orw &thorn;e nombre of 1 ; y sette &thorn;er a prikke <MILESTONE
N="32b" UNIT="folio">at my foote; &thorn;an goo [y] ner to &thorn;e tour, &amp; y see hym &thorn;orw at &thorn;e poynt of 2, &amp; &thorn;ere y sette a-no&thorn;er prikke; &amp;
<PB N="53">y be-holde how 1 hath hym to 12, &amp; &thorn;er fynde y &thorn;at yt hath hym
twelfe sithes ; &thorn;an be-holde y how 2 hath hym to 12, &amp; &thorn;ou 
schalt fynde it sexe sy&thorn;es; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;at [as] 
12 [above] 6 [is &thorn;e] numbre of 6, Ry&yogh;t so is &thorn;e space be-twen &thorn;i too 
prikkis &thorn;e space of 6 tymes &thorn;yn altitude. &amp; note, &thorn;at at &thorn;e ferste altitude of 1, &thorn;ou settest a prikke, &amp; aftyrward, whan &thorn;ou [seest] hym at 2, &thorn;er &thorn;ou settest an-o&thorn;er prikke, &thorn;an &thorn;ou fyndest betwen too prikkys [60] fett; &thorn;an &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;at [10 is &thorn;e 6-party of 
60.  And &thorn;en is 10 fete] &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e tour.  [For] o&thorn;er poyntis, 
&yogh;if yt fylle in <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">vmbra versa</FOREIGN>, as &thorn;us: y sette caas it fill vppon [2], &amp; at &thorn;e secunde vppon [3]; &thorn;an schalt &thorn;ou fynde &thorn;at [2] is [6] partyes of 
12; [and 3 is 4 partyes of 12]; &thorn;an passe&thorn; 6 4, be nombre of 2; so ys 
&thorn;e space be[twen] too prikkes twyes &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e tour. &amp; &yogh;if 
&thorn;e differens were &thorn;ries, &thorn;an schulde it be [&thorn;re] tymes; &amp; &thorn;us mayst &thorn;ou werke fro 2 to
12; &amp; &yogh;if yt <MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="folio">be 4, 4 tymes; or 5, 5 tymes, &amp; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">sic de ceteris</FOREIGN>. </P></DIV1><DIV1
ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
	<HEAD>43. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra [Recta].</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>An o&thorn;er maner of wyrkyng be <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">vmbra [recta]</FOREIGN>.  &YOGH;if it so be 
&thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst nat come to &thorn;e baas of &thorn;e tour, yn &thorn;is maner 
&thorn;ou schalt werke.  Sette &thorn;i Rewle vppon [1] till &thorn;ou see &thorn;e altitude, &amp; sette at &thorn;i foot a prikke. &thorn;an sette &thorn;i Rewle vppon 2, &amp; be-holde what ys &thorn;e diff[e]rense be-twen 1 and 2, &amp; &thorn;ou shalt fynde &thorn;at it is 1. &thorn;an mete &thorn;e space be-twen too prikkes, &amp; &thorn;at ys &thorn;e 12 partie of &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e tour; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;er were 2, yt were &thorn;e 6 partye; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;er were 3, &thorn;e 4 partye, &amp; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">sic deinceps</FOREIGN>.  And note, &yogh;if it were 5, yt were &thorn;e 5 party of 12 ; &amp; 7, 7 party of 12 ; and note, at &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;i conclusioun, adde &thorn;e stature of &thorn;yn heythe.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.Digby.72" TYPE="section"><PB N="54">

<HEAD>44. Another maner conclusion, to knowe the mene mote &amp; &thorn;e
argumentis of any planete.  To know the mene mote &amp; the argumentis 
of euery planete fro &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere, from day to day,
from owre to owre, And from smale fraccionis infinite.</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">[Ad cognoscendum medios motus &amp; argumenta de hora in horam
cuiuslibet planete, de anno in annum, de die in diem.]</HEAD><P>In this maner shalt &thorn;ou worche: consider thy rote furst, <MILESTONE
N="106" UNIT="folio">the wyche is made the begynning of the tabelis fro the &yogh;ere of owre lord
1397, &amp; entere hit in-to thy slate for the laste merydye of December;
and &thorn;an consider &thorn;e &yogh;ere of ovre lord, what is &thorn;e 
date, &amp; be-hold whe&thorn;er thy date be more or lasse &thorn;an &thorn;e &yogh;ere 1397.  And yf hit so be &thorn;at hit be more, loke how many [&yogh;eris] hit passith, &amp; with so many entere into thy tabelis in &thorn;e furst lyne &thorn;er as is wreten <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">anni  collecti &amp; expansi</FOREIGN>.  And loke [where] the same planet is wreten in the hede
of thy tabele, and than [loke] what &thorn;ou findest in directe of the same
&yogh;ere of owre lord wyche is passid, be hit 8, or 9, or 10, [or what
nombre &thorn;at euere it be, tyl &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou come to 
20, or] 40, or 60.  And that &thorn;ou fyndest in directe [wryte] in thy slate vnder thy rote,
&amp; adde hit [to-geder], and &thorn;at is thy mene mote, for the laste
meridian of the december, for the same &yogh;ere wyche &thorn;at &thorn;ou 
[hast] purposid.  And yf hit so be [&thorn;at] hit passe 20, consider welle 
&thorn;at fro [1] to 20 ben <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">anni expansi</FOREIGN>, And fro 20 to 3000 ben <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">anni collecti</FOREIGN>; and yf thy nombere passe 20, &thorn;an take &thorn;at &thorn;ou findest in 
directe of 20, &amp; yf hit be more, as 6 or 18, than take &thorn;at &thorn;ou findist in 
directe there-of, that is to sayen, signes, degreis, Minutes, &amp; secundis, and
adde [to-gedere] vn-to thy rote; and thus to make rotes; and note,
<PB N="55">&thorn;at yf hit <MILESTONE N="106b" UNIT="folio">so be [&thorn;at] the &yogh;ere of ovre lord be [lasse] than the rote, wyche is the &yogh;ere of ovre lord 1397, than shalt &thorn;ou write in the same wyse furst thy rote in thy slate, and after entere in-to thy table in the same &yogh;ere [&thorn;at] be lasse, as I tau&yogh;th be-fore; and &thorn;an consider how many signes, degrees, Minutes, &amp; secundis thyne entrynge conteynith.  And so be that [&thorn;er] be 2 entres, than adde hem togeder, &amp; after with-drawe hem from the rote, the &yogh;ere of ovre lord 1397; and the
residue &thorn;at lewyth is thy mene mote fro the laste mer[y]die of
December, the wyche &thorn;ou haste purposid; and yf hit so be &thorn;at 
&thorn;ou wolt weten thy mene mote [for] eny day, or [for] ony fraccion of day,
in &thorn;is maner &thorn;ou shalt worche. make thy rote fro the laste day of
Decembere in &thorn;e maner as I tha&yogh;the, and afterward behold how many
monythis, dayes, &amp; howris ben passid from [&thorn;e] merydye of Decembere 
&amp; with that entere [with &thorn;e] laste moneth &thorn;at is ful passid, 
and take &thorn;at &thorn;ou findest in directe of hym, &amp; wryte hit in 
thy slate; &amp; entere with as mony dayes as be more, and wryte &thorn;at &thorn;ou findest in directe of the same planete &thorn;at &thorn;ou worchyst fore; and in 
&thorn;e same wyse in-to &thorn;e table of howris, for hovris &thorn;at ben 
passid, and adde alle these to thy rote; and the <MILESTONE N="107" UNIT="folio">residue is the mene mote for the same day &amp; &thorn;e same hovre.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.Digby.72" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>45. Another manere to knowe the mene mote.</HEAD><P>Whan &thorn;ou wolte make the mene mote of eny planete to be by
arsechieles tables, take thy rote, the wyche is for the &yogh;ere of ovre
lord 1397; and yf so be that thy &yogh;ere be passid the date, wryte that
date / and than write that nombere of the &yogh;eris.  &thorn;an wyth-drawe 
&thorn;e &yogh;eris oute of the &yogh;eris that ben passid that rote. 
Ensampulle as thus : the &yogh;ere of ovre lord 1400, I-wryton precise, my 
rote; &thorn;an wrote I
<PB N="56">furst 1400.  And vnder that nombere I wrote a 1397; &thorn;an withdrowe I the 
laste nombere owte of &thorn;at, and &thorn;an fond I &thorn;e residue was
3 &yogh;ere; I wyst &thorn;at 3 &yogh;ere was passid fro the rote, &thorn;e wyche was
wreten in my tabelis. Than after-ward so&yogh;th I in my tabelis &thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">annis col1ectis &amp; expansis</FOREIGN>, &amp; amonge myne expanse &yogh;eris fond I 3 &yogh;ere. &thorn;an toke I alle &thorn;e signes, degreis, &amp; minutes, 
&thorn;at I fond directe vnder &thorn;e same planete &thorn;at I wro&yogh;th 
fore, &amp; wrote so many signes degreis, &amp; Minutes in my slate, &amp; 
after-ward added I too signes, degreis, Minutes, &amp; Secundis, &thorn;e 
wiche I fond in my rote the &yogh;ere of owre lord 1397; And kepte the residue; &amp; &thorn;an had I the mene mote for &thorn;e laste day of Decembere. And yf &thorn;ou woldest wete &thorn;e mene  mote ofany planete in March, Aprile, or may, o&thorn;er in any o&thorn;er tyme or monyth of the &yogh;ere, loke how many monethes &amp; dayes <MILESTONE
N="107b" UNIT="folio">ben passid from &thorn;e laste day of Decembere, the &yogh;ere of owre lord 1400; and soe
with monithis &amp; dayes entere in-to &thorn;y table &thorn;er &thorn;ou 
findist thy mene mote I-wreten in monethis &amp; dayes, and take alle 
&thorn;e signes, degrees, Minutes, &amp; secundis &thorn;at &thorn;ou findest I-wrete in directe of thy monethis, and [adde] to signes, degreis, Minutes, &amp; secundis &thorn;at 
&thorn;ou findest with thy rote &thorn;e &yogh;ere of ovre lord 1400, and the 
residue &thorn;at leuyth is &thorn;e mene mote for that same day. And note 
yf hit so be that &thorn;ou woldest [wete &thorn;e] mene mote in ony &yogh;ere &thorn;at is lasse &thorn;an thy rote, with-drawe &thorn;e nombere of so many &yogh;eris as hit is lasse 
&thorn;an &thorn;e &yogh;ere of ovre lord a 1397, &amp; kepe &thorn;e 
residue; &amp; so many &yogh;eris, monythis, &amp; dayes entere
in-to thy tabelis of thy mene mote.  And take alle the signes,
degreis, and Minutes, [and] Secundis, &thorn;at &thorn;ou findest in directe 
of alle &thorn;e &yogh;eris, monythis, &amp; dayes, &amp; wryte hem in &thorn;y 
slate; and abowe &thorn;ilke nombere write &thorn;e signes, degreis, Minutes, 
&amp; secundis, &thorn;e wyche &thorn;ou findest with thy rote &thorn;e &yogh;ere of ovre lord a l397; &amp; with-drawe alle &thorn;e nethere signis &amp; degreis fro &thorn;e signes 
&amp; degrees, Minutes, &amp; Secundis of o&thorn;er signes with thy rote, 
and thy residue &thorn;at lewyth is thy mene mote for &thorn;at day.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section"><PB N="57">

<HEAD>4la. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra Recta.</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE
N="34b" UNIT="folio"><P>&YOGH;if &thorn;i rewle falle vppon &thorn;e 8 poynt on ri&yogh;t schadwe, 
&thorn;an make &thorn;i figure of 8; &thorn;an loke how moche space of feet ys be-twen 
&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e tour, &amp; multiplie &thorn;at be 12, &amp; whan &thorn;ou 
[hast] multiplied it, &thorn;an diuide yt be &thorn;e same nombre of 8, &amp; kepe &thorn;e residue, &amp; adde &thorn;erto 4 vp to &thorn;yn eye to &thorn;e residue, &amp; &thorn;at schal be &thorn;e verry hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e tour.  &amp; &thorn;us mayst &thorn;ou werke on &thorn;e same wyse, fro 1 to 12.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>41b. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra Recta.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>An-o&thorn;er maner of werkyng vppon &thorn;e same syde.  Loke vppon
whych poynt &thorn;i Rewle falli&thorn; whan &thorn;ou seest &thorn;e top of 
&thorn;e tour &thorn;orow too litil holes, &amp; mete &thorn;an &thorn;e space fro &thorn;i foot to &thorn;e baas of &thorn;e tour; &amp; ry&yogh;t <MILESTONE
N="36" UNIT="folio">as the nombre of &thorn;y poynt hath hym-self to 12, 
ry&yogh;t so &thorn;e mesure be-twen &thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e tour ha&thorn; hym-self to 
&thorn;e hei&yogh;te of &thorn;e same tour.  Ensample : y sette caas &thorn;i rewle falle vpon 8, &thorn;an ys 8 to-&thorn;ridd partyes of 12; so &thorn;e space ys &thorn;e too-&thorn;ridd partyes of &thorn;e tour.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>42a. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vmbra Versa.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>To knowe &thorn;e [heyth by &thorn;y] poyntes of <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">umbra versa</FOREIGN>.  &YOGH;if  &thorn;y rewle falle vppon 3, whan &thorn;ou seest &thorn;e top of &thorn;e tour / 
sett a prikke &thorn;ere-as &thorn;i foot stont; &amp; goo ner tyl &thorn;ou mayst see 
&thorn;e same top at &thorn;e poynt of 4, &amp; sette &thorn;er ano&thorn;er lyk prikke / &thorn;an mete how many foot ben be-twen &thorn;e too prikkis, &amp; adde &thorn;e leng&thorn;e vp to &thorn;yn eye &thorn;er-to ; &amp; &thorn;at schal be &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e tour.  And note, &thorn;at 3 ys four&thorn;e party of 12, &amp; 4 is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde party of 12.  Now passe&thorn; 4 &thorn;e nombre of 3 be &thorn;e distaunce of 1; &thorn;erfore &thorn;e same space, wy&thorn; &thorn;yn hey&yogh;t to
<PB N="58">&thorn;yn eye, ys &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e tour. &amp; &yogh;if it so 
be &thorn;at &thorn;er be 2 or 3 distaunce in &thorn;e nombres, so schulde 
&thorn;e mesures be-twen &thorn;e prikkes be twyes or &thorn;ries &thorn;e 
hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e tour.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>43a. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad cognoscendum  altitudinem alicuius rei per vmbram [rectam].</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE
N="36b" UNIT="folio"><P>To knowe &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;ynges, &yogh;if &thorn;ou mayst 
[nat] come to &thorn;e bas of a &thorn;yng. sette &thorn;y rewle vppon what &thorn;ou 
wylt, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou may see &thorn;e topp of &thorn;e &thorn;yng &thorn;orw &thorn;e too holes, &amp; make a marke &thorn;er &thorn;y foot stande&thorn;; and goo neer or for&thorn;er / till &thorn;ou mayst see &thorn;orw ano&thorn;er poynt, &amp; marke &thorn;er a-no&thorn;er marke; &amp; loke &thorn;an what ys &thorn;e differense be-twen &thorn;e too poyntes in &thorn;e scale; &amp; ri&yogh;t as &thorn;at difference ha&thorn; hym to 12, ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e space be-twen &thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e too markys ha&thorn; hym to &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e &thorn;yng.  Ensample : y set caas &thorn;ou seest it &thorn;orw a poynt of 4 ; aftyr, at &thorn;e poynt of 3.  Now passi&thorn; &thorn;e nombre 
of 4 &thorn;e nombre of 3 be &thorn;e difference of 1, and ri&yogh;t as &thorn;is 
difference 1 ha&thorn; hym-self to 12, ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e mesure be-twen &thorn;e too markis ha&thorn; hym to &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;e &thorn;yng, puttyng to &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;i-self to &thorn;yn eye ; &amp; &thorn;us mayst &thorn;ou werke fro 1 to 12.
</P></DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.E.2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>42b. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Per vmbram versam.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Fur&thorn;ermore, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt knowe in <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">vmbra versa</FOREIGN> / be &thorn;e craft of
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">vmbra recta</FOREIGN>, y suppose &thorn;ou take &thorn;e altitude at &thorn;e poynt of 4, &amp;
makest a marke, &amp; &thorn;ou goost neer tyl &thorn;ou hast yt at &thorn;e poynt of 3, &amp; &thorn;an makyst <MILESTONE
N="37" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ou &thorn;er an-no&thorn;er mark. &thorn;an muste &thorn;ou deuide 144 be eche of &thorn;e poyntes be-fornseyd, [as] &thorn;us : &yogh;if &thorn;ou deuide 144
<PB N="59">be [4,] &amp; &thorn;e nombre &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;er-of schal be 
36, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou deuide 144 be 3, &amp; &thorn;e nombre &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;er-of schal be 48, &thorn;anne loke what ys &thorn;e difference be-twen 36 &amp; 48, &amp; &thorn;er schalt &thorn;ou fynde 12; and ry&yogh;t as 12 ha&thorn; hym to 12, ry&yogh;t so &thorn;e space be-twen too prikkes ha&thorn; hym to &thorn;e altitude of &thorn;e &thorn;yng.
</P>
</DIV1><DIV1 ANA="MS.Bodley.619" TYPE="section">

<HEAD>46. For to knowe at what houre of &thorn;e day, or of the night, shal be
Flode or ebbe.</HEAD><P>First wite thou certeinly, how that haven stondith, that thou list
to werke fore ; &thorn;at is to say in whiche place of the firmament the
mone beyng, maki&thorn; fulle see.  Than awayte &thorn;ou redily in what
degree of &thorn;e zodiak &thorn;at &thorn;e mone at &thorn;at tyme is ynne.  
Bringe furth than &thorn;e labelle, &amp; sett the point therof in &thorn;at same cost 
&thorn;at the mone maki&thorn; flode, and sett &thorn;ou &thorn;ere &thorn;e degre of &thorn;e mone according wi&thorn; &thorn;e egge of &thorn;e label.  Than afterward awayte where is than &thorn;e degre of the sonne, at &thorn;at tyme.  Remeue &thorn;ou than &thorn;e label fro the mone, &amp; bringe &amp; sette [it] iustly vpon &thorn;e degre of &thorn;e sonne. And &thorn;e point of &thorn;e label shal &thorn;an declare to &thorn;e, at what houre of &thorn;e day or of &thorn;e night shal be flode.  And &thorn;ere also maist &thorn;ou wite by &thorn;e same point of &thorn;e label, whe&thorn;ir it be, at &thorn;at same, flode or ebbe, or half flode, or quarter flode, or ebbe, or half or quarter ebbe ; or ellis at what houre it was last, or shalbe next by night or by day, &thorn;ou &thorn;an [maist] esely
<PB N="60">knowe, etc.  Fur&thorn;ermore if it so be &thorn;at thou happe to worke for 
&thorn;is matere aboute &thorn;e tyme of coniunccioun, bringe fur&thorn;e &thorn;e 
degre of &thorn;e mone wi&thorn; &thorn;e labelle to &thorn;at coste as it is before seyde. 
but than &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ou may not bringe fur&thorn;e &thorn;e label fro &thorn;e degre of &thorn;e mone as &thorn;ou dide before; For-why the sonne is &thorn;an in &thorn;e same degre with the mone.  And so &thorn;ou may at &thorn;at tyme by &thorn;e point of the labelle vnremevid knowe &thorn;e houre of &thorn;e flode or of &thorn;e ebbe as it is before seyd, &amp;c.  And euermore as &thorn;ou findest &thorn;e mone passe fro &thorn;e sonne, so remeve &thorn;ou &thorn;e labelle &thorn;an fro &thorn;e 
degre of &thorn;e mone, and bringe it to the degre of &thorn;e sonne.  And worke &thorn;ou &thorn;an as &thorn;ou dide before, etc.  Or ellis knowe &thorn;ou what houre it is &thorn;at &thorn;ou art inne, by &thorn;in instrument.  Than bringe &thorn;ou furthe fro thennes &thorn;e labelle and ley it vpon &thorn;e degre of &thorn;e mone, and &thorn;erby may &thorn;ou wite also whan it was flode, or whan it wol be next, be it nyght or day; &amp;c.
</P></DIV1></DIV0>


